animal.description: Are you looking for a dog that's not the 'typical' dog? One that is unique in every way, goofy and lovable, and doesn't need to go on daily runs in the park? You've come to the right place - meet Buster! This handsome little guy will warm your heart when he leans on you for pets, and keep your feet warm while you're stuck on that hours-long zoom meeting, and provide endless entertainment with his silly personality. Buster is a quiet pup who would thrive in a low-activity home. He loves routine, and is very easy to live with! He has a few neurological quirks that make some things a little tough for him - for example, he's a little off-balance (hey, not everyone is athletic!), and he will let you know when he's anxious by spinning in circles. We think those quirks make him even more endearing, and he's been working on some training exercises to be the best dog he can be. However, his vision isn't the best, but his excellent sniffer and super-sharp hearing make up for that! He enjoys sniffing around for treats hiding in the grass or just lying in the sunshine soaking up the rays. He's great at entertaining himself with toys and doesn't demand too much - just someone to love! If you're interested in learning more about this special pup, we'd love to tell you all about him! Buster is one-of-a-kind and would be a wonderful companion... and did we mention how handsome he is?! Come meet Buster today!
animal.name: Buster

animal.description: If you're looking for a new affectionate cuddle buddy who always wants to be right by your side and give you lots of kisses, then keep reading because Ocelot is your guy! This sweet, faithful, gentleman wants nothing more than to just be near his people every hour of every day, whether it be curled up on his bed or snuggled up on the couch with you. He is super mellow and loving, and likes to just snooze by your side (he makes the perfect quiet work-from-home buddy!). His past family had to give him up because they were traveling too much, otherwise they would've kept him forever as he was the perfect family dog. Ocelot does have an old, healed injury on his right paw and some arthritis in his elbow, but they don't slow him down one bit! He has the cutest gait and will paw at you endlessly for more attention and treats, all the while gazing at you with his deep, soulful eyes. He loves to explore the world and spend time outside - sleeping in the sun, sniffing all the new scents, and happily wiggle-worming in the grass. Ocelot is fully house-trained when let out 2-3 times a day, and is working on crate-training. He adores his 9yo and 16yo kids, and loves to romp around with his 2yo doggy sister in the living room. He has done incredibly well with some younger visitors, calmly greeting them and offering his belly for rubs. He is such a smart boy and very food-motivated, and is an absolute dream to walk on a leash. He is working on not jumping on people, counters, or couches uninvited, and he learned VERY quickly. But, he will not object if you let your pup pals on the couch. He has not been observed around cats yet, so we do not know how he will react to them. With his gorgeous brindle coat and kindhearted personality, Ocelot is the whole package! His ideal home would not have any stairs so he doesn't have to stress his joints, and preferably a yard so he can sunbathe to his heart's content. If you have room in your home and your heart for this good boy, come meet Ocelot, and he'll show you how much love he has to give!
animal.name: Ocelot

animal.description:
Meet Minnie!

Minnie is a sweetie senior Min Pin who loves to burrow under her blanket in a cozy bed or snuggle up to you on the couch. She's vision impaired, but is a brave explorer and is learning how to navigate in her new surroundings. She also loves to explore the backyard. She will give you a little bark when she's ready to come back in the house and needs help finding the door.

Minnie is comfortable around all dogs. She doesn't bother anyone.

She would be better suited to a forever home with no stairs to make her life comfy unless you are prepared to carry up and downstairs. But baby gates around the stairs would be a must for her safety.

Minnie is somewhat independent. We think Minnie just got use to folks ignoring her and learned to fend for herself. Now she is enjoying our snuggles and sweet talk. We're confident she'll become more settled and less shy as she gets to know and love her new family!

Minnie sleeps on a big fluffy bed in an xpen. Minnie prefers to do her business outside. She will need your assistance getting outside until she learns her way to the door. Are you ready to give Minnie her best chapter ever?

Minnie is 11 years old and 11 pounds.

More photos: https://flic.kr/s/aHsmTAehLp

Minnies Adoption fee is $255.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
Our kennels are closed to the public, and we will only be responding to pet inquiries accompanying an online adoption application. We appreciate your patience as you wait for an email response once you submit your application. Adoption appointments are scheduled in the order that approved applications are received. You can find our adoption procedures and online application at warmhearts.org/adopt.

Belle was surrendered to the shelter when found stray with a few of her babies in tow. We do not have any background information. Belle has really come out of her shell and is enjoying the affection of staff and volunteers. Belle's estimated DOB is 8/1/2017. She is likely done growing in size at 45 pounds. We cannot be sure if Belle is house trained; she walks great on a leash.

HSPC's adoption fee is seventy-five-dollars through December 31, 2020, unless stated otherwise within the pet's description. At times, our adoption fees are lowered during special events that are posted to our website or Facebook page. Every pet that is available for adoption has been spayed/neutered, microchipped, and is up-to-date on vaccinations including heartworm preventative (canines). Adopters are required to schedule a wellness exam with their veterinarian at their cost within 7 days of adoption.

Please only submit one application. Once you are contacted by email, you will have an opportunity to provide us with any additional animal(s) under consideration.

animal.description:
Hello Hoomans! I am Shadow, I am about 3 years old and I weigh 50 lbs.. My life in north Georgia was completely turned upside down because I lost my Dad, and then 6 months later I lost my mom. I was adopted by them when I was about 7 months old and they went through my teenage years with me. They would always say that I was lucky that they loved me so much because I was a handful. I have matured quite a bit, but I am still an active pup and need someone who is confident, and calm, and if they have another pup in the home that's like that too, it makes me feel a lot better. :) Young kids scare me too. I ended up in daycare for about 60 days in the previous 4 months while my mom went in and out of the hospital, and it frazzled my nerves a little bit. I do a lot better in a calm home and I start to show my personality. 
I am neutered, up to date with my vaccines, microchipped, current on heartworm and flea preventatives. An application is required, no exceptions. My adoption fee is $350 and includes an adoption kit with a free bag of food and coupons for supplies. Please email petadopt@hotmail.com to get an adoption application for me. Thanks!

animal.description:
Hera is one of our favorite rescue dogs! We rescued Hera when she was very pregnant and living in the streets in a bad neighborhood in Tijuana. She was very shy and scared.

Now that all of Hera’s pups have left the nest, she is a completely different dog! She’s basically a puppy herself. She’s about 2-3 years old, very playful and athletic. She’s smart as a tack and would do great with an active family. 

She loves playing with her human and dog foster siblings. She is fully vaccinated and has an appointment to be fixed in February with SNPLA.

animal.description:
Welcome sweet Holly to Worthy Dog Rescue! Holly was a chained dog who was not only starved and neglected but was being beaten by her former owner. Neighbors were monitoring the situation and reached out to rescue for help. Thankfully, some local animal advocates in this rural area of SC were able to negotiate her surrender. Holly was emaciated when we took her in, weighing only 35lbs, heartworm positive, and full of parasites. She has been in our care for almost a month now and has come such a long way. She has gained 15lbs, her coat has filled in nicely, she's been spayed, and she will be treated for heartworm next week.

While Holly had a very rough early life, she still has a sweet, submissive nature and will be able to make a complete recovery with the right owner. She's excellent with other dogs and finds a lot of comfort in being around them. She is very affectionate with people once she gets to know them and will give you kisses for as long as you let her. Loud noises and sudden movements frighten her, which is understandable with her background. She was probably born outside and chained as a young puppy and got very little socialization or exposure to the outside world. She's still a young dog at only 1 to 1.5 years old and can look forward to a much better future.

Holly has been fostered with several other dogs in South Carolina and has done well as part of a pack. She's calm in the house and has good house manners, and is housetrained and crate trained. Her crate is her safe space when she gets scared of something. Holly is learning to walk on a leash and walks much better with another dog by her side. She can easily get startled when walking on leash, so we believe she would do best in a quiet neighborhood vs. an urban or active area.

Holly's foster mom describes her as having a moderate energy level and she's discovered her fondness for plush blankets and naptime on a comfy couch. She is fearful of meeting new people, especially men, and needs time to be comfortable with new things. She's not aggressive and would choose to flee or avoid any frightening situation if possible. She is doing better with her foster dad and will let him sit and pet her, but still won't come in the house if he opens the door.

When Holly hears loud or sudden noises, she will start shaking and hope to disappear...it's going to take time for her to adapt to home life and feel secure. She recently met the grandkids and was skittish around them because they were noisy and overly excited to meet her.

Holly really needs a patient owner and a calm environment to continue her rehabilitation. She is thriving at her foster home, having a nice big yard to romp in. She loves to zoom around the yard and is learning how to play with the other dogs. We think a home with another confident, social dog in a quiet suburban neighborhood is what Holly needs.

Holly will be coming to N. VA in early February. Apply today to learn more about her and welcome her home.

Preference will be given to:

Families with another social, confident dog in the home

Single-family home in a quiet neighborhood

Experience working with timid/fearful dogs

BREED ESTIMATE: AmStaff (Pittie) mix
GENDER: Female
APPROXIMATE WEIGHT: 44 lbs
APPROXIMATE AGE: ~ 1 to 1.5 years
COAT TYPE: Short
ADOPTION FEE: $400
OTHER INFO: utd on shots/spayed/microchipped/treated for heartworm
LOCATION: Mathews, NC

FOR MORE INFO OR TO ADOPT: Please go to https://adopt.worthydog.org and complete the application.

You can also help save dogs like this one by becoming a foster, providing a rescue dog with a temporary home and giving them the love and care they need until they are permanently adopted. Every person who fosters is directly responsible for saving the life of a dog, because we can only save as many dogs as we have foster families available to welcome them into their homes. If you think you might be interested in becoming a foster and want to learn more, please go to https://foster.worthydog.org and fill out an application.

Worthy Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue that primarily adopts to families in the DC Metro area.

HERSHEY is 5 yrs old and weighs 4.8 lbs; she is a dainty and tiny female Chihuahua with a beautiful pale cream and chocolate short coat. This little girl is microchipped, current on vaccines and is spayed. We feel that we must tell potential adopters that Hershey is a fear biter with a ferocious attitude. She is definitely a big dog in a little dogs body. If she likes you, you’re golden… if she doesn’t….well you can fill in the rest. Hershey was recently adopted and returned for attacking and biting. Hershey seems to be people selective. 

The perfect home will be with an EXPERIENCED Chihuahua owner who will be willing to seek out and work with a behaviorist if needed. We recommend that you leave her harness and leash on her during the transition period, that you use an x-pen so that you can easily get her out to potty, and that you purchase a little tent bed. That is her safe place. A doggie door would also be beneficial.

For companionship, we would prefer another small dog of like size and age in the home. Hershey is friendly with other dogs, she likes to be picked up and cuddled, but when she's in her tent bed she does not like to be picked up. Hershey is not a barker and we would consider Hershey to be a “tea cup” in terms of size which means that she can easily travel with you and she is potty trained using a doggie door.

Sweetieand Freckles!Sweetieand Freckles! What a lovely pair they be!

Sweetie, the little white Terrier mix, and Freckles, the not much bigger gorgeous Catahoula Hound mix, are best friends forever! Their owner passed away and they ended up running the streets together until a kind neighbor took them in, had them completely vetted, and called us to help find them a perfect home together! They must stay together as they are definitely a bonded pair. Not quite twinkies, but a bonded pair indeed.

Little Sweetieis the boss and Freckles is her right-hand gal. They are a hoot together!Sweetie is like an alarm clock for breakfast and dinner so you'd better be on time with both or she will let you know. Freckles is a bit cautious meeting new people, but warms up soon. They are both very very sweet and smart too! Both give the gentlest of kisses. Both are crate trained. Although they keep their crates clean and dry and appear to be housetrained which took a bit of work..

So, if you want some small, sweet, smart, funny, furry companions, this is the pair for you! Oh, did I tell you they are a hoot together? Check out their video below and be sure to turn up the sound.

Here you can see them in action...whirling dervishes... so much fun!!! https://youtu.be/fSYlYEK0MsM

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS:
Good with Children: Unknown
Good with Dogs: Unknown
Good with Cats: Unknown

IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.


Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.


At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.




NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
Oliver is a great dog and doesn't mind a home with cats. We find that unusual and endearing because Oliver is a a bit high energy but he's smart, so very smart! He knows sit, stay, plays fetch and tug of war, shakes with both paws and is potty trained crate trained! The studies say it takes 3 days to decompress, 3 weeks to trust and learn routines, and 3 months to be the dog they really are! We hope his fosters see it sooner, but Oliver is great and ready to go to his forever home. Because we are foster based, we require an approved application before a meet and greet can be scheduled. We think that is fair for our fosters so every meet and greet has the potential to result in an immediate adoption. The application is available on the rescue website and can be completed online.We work with many rescues and strive to find every rescued dog in our care a great home. Sometimes that means transferring that pet to another location where adoption may be more likely. We currently have partners in New York, Pennsylvania, and Vermont.

If you are interesting in meeting any of our pets, the process is to complete an application. It can be downloaded as a pdf document from our website and submitted by email to WindyRidgeRescue@gmail.com as a scanned document or as photos OR can be completed entirely online. Both links are in the header of our website.

Because we are foster based, we require an approved application to schedule a meet and greet. We feel that is fair to our fosters and rescues so every meet and greet can result in an adoption.

We do not have set adoption fees for dogs, but hope adopters will donate generously so we can rescue more. The medical care for every dog can easily exceed the adoption donation. Average adoption fees for dogs in the area range from $175 up to $450.

We ask for a minimum adoption donation of $50 for cats regardless of age. Each cat is up to date on vaccinations, dewormer, and microchipped. Larger donations are always welcome so we can rescue more. Medical care for each cat easily exceeds the minimum donation.

As with every rescue, our resources are limited and the need for rescue help is unlimited. Your generosity helps us to rescue more.

Adopting or fostering for a rescue frees up a space where a new rescue can reside.

If you can't adopt or foster, than please consider donating.

CRATE TRAINED:  Yes, but doesn’t care for it
LEASH TRAINED:  Yes

HOME W/ OTHER DOGS:           MALE:  Yes        FEMALE:  Yes

MONTHLY HEARTWORM DATE:  30th of each month
FOSTER HOME:  Angela,  lucybug15@yahoo.com
RESCUE #:  2020-12-29-03
BIO:   
Chip was turned into a shelter in southern Alabama by his previous owners who said they could not housebreak him after a year. We have had no problem with him so we suspect there were other reasons.

Chip had his dental and no teeth were lost. Yea!!!  Chip is a laid back and happy dog.  He is very friendly when he meets new dogs and people.  Chip loves his people and loves to snuggle.  He wants to be with you and does not understand when he is left behind.  He does not like the crate and will bark and cry when he has to go in.  We are working with him on this.  Chip will adjust when he learns your schedule and understands you will come back for him.

This little guy loves to play with toys.  He is a typical dachshund and will destroy them in a heartbeat!  Chip is starting to play a little with my other dachshund.  I think he will start doing zoomies with her soon.  Another thing Chip loves is car rides.  He is always ready to be your little co-pilot!

Chip has a few more pounds to lose but it should not be a problem because he loves to go on walks.  He is trained to a doggy door and has not had any accidents.  He does not mark in the house.  Chip will use ramps/stairs he cannot jump.

Our wish list for Chip includes:
•	A fenced yard
•	Another adult small breed dog to keep him company and cuddle with.
•	No apartments or high rises
•	Someone home a lot because he does not like to be left alone.
•	Someone patient until he learns the rules of the house.

If you want great companion and snuggle buddy then please fill out an application.   Please don’t make him wait for his forever home!!!

============== Information for All Dogs/Adopters ==============

If you have questions about this dog, please feel free to contact the foster home at the email address listed above.  They have the most up-to-date information concerning the dog and would be happy to answer any questions about the animal. 

We welcome out of state and Canadian adoptions, but we will not ship any dog via cargo.  You will have to make arrangements to pick up the dog or for them to go by ground transport.  If you choose transporting by either volunteers through our organization or by paid transporter, there will be an additional $45 fee added for the required Health Certificate. 

We will not adopt into CT, RI, NH, ME, or MA due to strict laws regarding importation of dogs into those states.  If you have an issue with this, you need to take this up with your legislatures.

To understand the adoption process through AADR, please review the Adoption Information on our home page.  Transportation options are outlined on that page in Step 3.

If you are interested in adopting this Dachshund please review Read Before You Adopt and then you can complete an Application.

THANK YOU FOR YOUR INTEREST IN A RESCUE.

Please don't let the distance stand in your way of finding your newest best friend. We have volunteers that will help your "new friend" get up and down the East Coast. We just can't get them from one Coast to the other but some day we hope to have enough volunteers to do that as well.  For now, please look for dogs on your coast.

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Ryder is an Shepherd / Husky mix that was rescued from a high kill shelter in Victor Valley CA. He is estimated to be around 1.5 years old, weighs about 60lbs and joined us on December 20th.

Foster Update: Ryder is a total snuggle bug with a lot of energy but is also very content laying by your feet. He does great with people and gets along well with the resident dog. They love to play. Ryder had no obedience skills and some puppy behavior that his fosters have been working on, he can get a little mouthy when he gets really excited and overstimulated. He's learned some basic commands and is now working on improving his duration without treats. He does ok in the crate when the resident dog is home but does get destructive when left completely alone so we think about dog in the home would be a huge plus and someone willing to continue to work with him on that.

Ryder would make a great hiking, running companion and will do best in an active home. He would prefer another dog in the home as he does better being left alone that way. He would also be a good candidate to go to work with you.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $500, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, and heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was rescued from euthanasia at a high-kill shelter in California and will be available for adoption in Seattle, once evaluated in a loving foster home in the greater Seattle area.

8 week old cattle dog mix from Tehama Co with special needs Little Koa was diagnosed with mega-esophagus, a condition in which the esophagus can not constrict and move food down on it's own. He will require a special feeding position to let gravity move the food for him. Typical, happy, playful puppy Loves playing with other dogs Doing great with potty training

If you are interested in adopting this dog please visit this link to get the adoption process started.

We hold adoption events from San Francisco to the South Bay. Most dogs will be ready to go home the day of the adoption event. We accept credit cards and cash for our adoption fees. While adoption events are a great showcase for these amazing dogs, you don't need an adoption event to adopt a dog. Check out our adoptable pups, submit an application, and then meet them at their foster home!

We try to post the dogs that are attending on Facebook before the event, please visit and like us on Facebook.

To View other dogs up for adoption please visit our website.

animal.description:
Meet Scotty!

Scotty is a 3 year old Pit/Weimaraner mix. He loves going on long walks and meeting new people people. His favorite spot to nap is inside of his crate on his comfy bed. Scotty can sometimes be nervous/shy around smaller children so we are requiring that he go to a home with high school aged children and up. We recommend him as an only dog as he needs time to be properly socialized. He shows no signs of leash reactivity, just excitement so he will do best with an experienced handler.
Scotty will make a great hiking buddy and he has a lot of love to give.

If you are interested in meeting Scotty, please submit your adoption application through our website istandwithmypack.org/adopt

animal.description:
Meet Sophie! Sophie appears to be a German Shepherd mix, about 6 years old. She is an affectionate sweet girl who loves to snuggle although she can be slightly nervous around new people. She is dog friendly and prefers more mellow dogs. She does have separation anxiety and so would do best in a home with another calm, confident dog to keep her company (unless her new "human" is always home). She has not been around cats but we assume she would be fine. She does well with poultry, horses, and other livestock. Sophie is not super playful although she loves going for walks. Instead, she prefers the finer things in life, like cuddling on the couch with her human. Sophie will only be adopted out to a home without children or older, considerate children (12+)

If you are interested in adopting Sophie, please submit an adoption application located on our website, coloradocaninerescue.org. We are asking for a $250 adoption donation. Sophie is spayed, housebroken, up to date on vaccinations, and microchipped.

CCR cannot hold dogs, arrange meet and greets or adopt out any dogs without a completed adoption application.

CCR cannot guarantee the breed composition or ages of our dogs as we usually have no history prior to them entering the shelter.

Dogs listed as potty trained may experience an adjustment period as they learn the routines in their new home.

animal.description:
Oakley lived his life mostly outdoors without much socialization. His family decided moving to a cold climate would be too hard on him and relinquished him to SCGRR. We believe he is a combination of flat coat retriever and a herding breed such as Australian Shepard. He is very smart and energetic even for 9 years old. He quickly bonds to his humans and seeks comfort from them whenever he is nervous. He loves car rides, being rubbed under the chin and along his back. And he has the most adorable white paws!!!
 
Oakley will need several weeks to settle into his new home. Once adjusted, Oakley’s soulful eyes will melt your heart and he will love you to the moon and back. He loves exercise and affection and toys. He is looking for a calm, experienced and confident adult human (or humans) to trust and help him adjust to the bigger world around him. When you are working from home, he will lay at your feet calmly. But he is game for a jog or hike also. He is house broken and affectionate. He is a picky eater but salmon, chicken and cheese are quite appreciated! He is very dog reactive so should be an only dog in a community where he can work on his leash skills at some distance from other dogs. He also has a prey drive so no other pets in the home other than maybe a fish! No cats, bunnies or other small critters. If you have critters in your yard, he will suss them out for you and maybe dig a few holes if they live underground. Young children under 15 are also not a good idea. A quiet home would be best without a lot of new experiences (aka camping trips) or visitors for quite some time.
 
After adjusting to his new home environment, Oakley needs a commitment to slow and patient socialization to adjust to the world at large. He is leash reactive and at the moment is staying far away from other dogs and even small children in push cars. He will try to chase cats and other creatures. A willingness to work with a positive reinforcement behaviorist or experience in dealing with a dog like Oakley is important unless you live a more rural existence where such interactions might not be so critical. Oakley has mostly known his back yard. As a first step on his journey, he is learning to “self soothe” in his foster home – finding ways to calm himself down rather than seeking human comfort – something that will help him become a more balanced dog.
 
If you are ready to give this nervous but loving dude all the patience and guidance he deserves, please contact his friend Lori at regadog1010@gmail.com and tell her about how he will spend his days with you. Oakley is currently residing in Westminster, CA.
 
As a 9 year old, the minimum adoption donation for Oakely is $350

**PLEASE NOTE THAT WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO COVER AND ADOPT OUT TO HOMES IN THE SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA AREA**

animal.description:
Hello

My name is King Linus or just Linus is ok with me.

I am a special pup that is in search of that special family.

I will need a family that is willing to learn how to express my bladder for me. My foster mom does that for me 3 times a day and she said that I am the easiest one that she has ever had to do and she is willing to teach anyone how to do it.

I am a big cuddle bug. I always want to be around you.

I do like to play with my siblings at the house ( both cats and dogs) .

I think I would be ok with little kids but I haven't been around them before.

I only say I think because like I mentioned before..I am a special dog.

Any number of things could have happened but I try my hardest to use my back legs as much as I can. I dont have control of my bladder- which is why I need help expressing it.

I do have a wheelchair but if I had to have a preference, I would like to try to use all my legs to walk. However if you like to go on some small walks, I will use my wheelchair because once I am in it, I can go fast:)

I am only 5 pounds and almost 2 years old. I am neutered and up to date on my shots. My adoption fee is $190 and does not include the $11 PACC license transfer fee. My wheelchair/cart comes with me too.

animal.description:
My name is Mora and I'm 4 years old. I'm a long haired shepherd with a beautiful silky coat. My foster mom says I'm a combination of a super model, professional ball player and rocket scientist. I walk well on a leash, enjoy car rides and taking adventures.

I know my basic commands and am very eager to learn new things. I take treats gently from your hand and am learning to be patient and wait for my food. My foster mom says I am very smart and when treats are involved I can train all day. Sometimes my foster mom wonders who is training who. I'm a typical female shepherd so I know my own mind but I am loving and very sweet.

I like dogs and hanging out with my foster pack. I've been to the park on pack walks with other dogs and I did great. I'm learning how to settle when I'm out of my crate and need some supervision but, I am not destructive. I would like to be an only dog so I can get lots of love and attention that I never got when I was a puppy. I love petting and affection.

From my foster mom: Mora is a wonderful girl. She has come so far and learning more each day. She is learning to trust and starting to enjoy life. Mora is a happy girl, very confident with great nerves and a wonderful temperament. At times, she can be pushy but that's because she is a confident girl but, with light verbal correction she listens. She is very affectionate and super sweet. Mora is a beautiful girl and needs an
EXPERIENCED HANDLER THAT HAS OWNED PURE BRED GERMAN SHEPHERDS
and understands the intelligence of the breed. Mora requires exercise each day which includes ball play in her fenced backyard. She is an excellent companion and will sit next to you while you are gardening. Did I mention Mora LOVES vegetables? Mora is good with children, BUT WE WILL NOT PLACE HER IN A HOME WITH CHILDREN UNDER 16.

Mora is
spayed, microchipped, current on vaccinations, on heartworm preventative, crate trained, leash and basic obedience trained and house broken. If you are interested in this beautiful, affectionate girl, please fill out an online application at the
https://form.jotform.com/bmsr/application
If you have any questions, you can contact Donna J. at
BMSR1313@gmail.com

.

animal.description:
NEO

Spaniel Mix |

Small (11-25 lbs.)

| 10 Months / Male Neutered | Available for Adoption

Neo is a quirky and sweet little puppy who is about one year old. He is 90% angel and 10% crazy! Neo is really enjoying his life with his foster family. He gets along great with the other dogs in his foster home, but is not too fond of the neighborhood cats. He loves to run and play rough and tumble, but listens to the older dogs when they ask him to calm down. He shares toys and enjoys a good game of tug-o-war. Neo is learning commands and has mastered "Sit," "Shake," and "Come." He loves to play fetch and is really awesome at it! He is very patient and gentle when taking treats and is happy to go to bed in his crate at night. He loves car rides and is a good road trip companion.

Neo is working on a few issues, including house training. Like many puppies, he loves being outside so much that he forgets to do his business. He is also a bit protective of his resources. For Neo this means his family and especially his foster dad. He is skeptical of strangers and takes time to warm up to new people. But once he does, he is loving and playful. We are working on letting him know he can let his guard down. Due to his resource protecting and somewhat unpredictable reactions, we recommend that Neo be placed in a home with older children (teens and up) who have dog experience. Neo would also do best with a fur sibling to help show him the ropes.

Please visit our website if you would like to submit an adoption application.

Neo's Adoption Donation Fee is $325. Neo is neutered, current on all vaccinations, has received a wellness exam and is microchipped.

animal.description:
Meet Krissy girl!  She's adorable, extremely friendly and cuddly.  She and her furbrother Zuki were rescued from an apt. fire during the  Christmas season.  We're trying to find a family that will welcome them both since they're bonded. They're both seniors, but still have a lot of love to give! 

Krissy is 12 yrs old but you wouldn't know it, she still has quite a bit of playful spunk left in her, she acts much younger than she is.  She's such a doll, affectionate and sweet, definitely a cuddle bug! :)  She's a Teddy Bear Chihuahua/Doxi mix, so low to the ground and fast! lol  She's very playful, loves to play with her toys and other dogs, and her favorite thing to do is cuddle with her humans. :)  She's fixed, microchipped, current on shots, heart worm tested and a blood panel done to ensure she's a healthy girl!  

Zuki is approx. 14 yrs. old, neutered, microchipped, current on shots, heart worm tested, as well as a blood panel to make sure he was healthy.  He's old but he's still got spunk! lol  He actually sleeps most of the day and loves to cuddle...if you're looking for a lap dog, he's your guy!  A trait his sister Krissy enjoys too! 

If interested in meeting Zuki and Krissy, please visit our website at, www.doggonerescue.com, to fill out our adoption application, that'll get the ball rolling! If you have any questions about these two furkids please don't hesitate to let us know, we look for to hearing from you!

Delilah was rescued from a Kansas City shelter four years ago, to a loving mom. Sadly, her mom has since had some serious health issues that meant she had to move into assisted living and could not take care of this sweet dog. Delilah is now being fostered in St. Louis, Missouri and is doing very well. 

She is 10 years old, but do not let her age fool you! She is still an active dog that loves walks and especially loves her honking pig toy, but she loves food more than anything else in the world. Delilah is currently 65 lbs, but she is on a weight-loss journey and she has already lost almost 7 1/2#!  Despite being overweight, the vet describes her as “healthy as a horse” and she is spayed and up to date on all her shots. 

Delilah will need a home without cats, small children, or other dogs, but she loves her humans fiercely and even smiles at you when you get home. To inquire about adopting this sweet girl, please fill out an application here!  www.australianshepherdsfurever.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
This boy is a sweetheart and just waiting to be your best buddy. Tatum is strong but trainable on the leash since he LOVES treats. He will sit on command and offer his paw; and he was so enthusiastic about getting a treat that he would sometimes even stand on his back legs like a human but not jump on me. So cute! He loved playing fetch with a ball and tug rope. He did his business outside so probably house trained. Tatum certainly seemed eager to please and loved affection. He has the softest and most beautiful color coat of fur and just waiting for some good lovin' from an individual or family that has a secure fenced in yard. He seemed to be fine with other dogs when we had him on leash and encountering others but always a good idea if you are considering adoption to do a "meet and greet" with your own dog(s). He has been fostered and got a good report and even on his shelter behavioral assessment he got good grades. Please come in to meet this boy in person and find out more about him from our adoption counselors and foster coordinator. I bet you will fall in love with this personable and playful guy. 

Observations by volunteer S. Shaffer - 2/1/21

animal.description:
Meet Zuki boy!  He's actually the first skipper breed I've met that's been nice! ;)    They can all be a little feisty at times, but Zuki is a sweetheart. He can be a little nervous upon meeting people, but warms up quickly, especially if treats are involved! lol  

He's approx. 14 yrs. old, neutered, microchipped, heart worm tested, as well as a blood panel to make sure he was healthy.  He's old but he's still got spunk! lol  He actually sleeps most of the day and loves to cuddle...if you're looking for a lap dog, he's your guy!  A trait his sister Krissy enjoys, she enjoys too.  She and his fursister Krissy were rescued from an apt. fire.  They're bonded so we're trying to find a home to welcome the both. :)  

Krissy is 12 yrs old but you wouldn't know it, she still has quite a bit of playful spunk left in her, she acts much younger than she is.  She's such a doll, extremely affectionate and sweet.  She's definitely a mix!  We were told she's a Teddy Bear Chihuahua/Doxi mix, so low to the ground but fast! lol  She's very playful, loves to play with her toys and other dogs, and her favorite thing to do is cuddle with her humans. :) She's extremely friendly. 

If interested in meeting Zuki and Krissy, please visit our website at, www.doggonerescue.com, to fill out our adoption application, that'll get the ball rolling! If you have any questions about these two furkids, don't hesitate to let us know, we look for to hearing from you!

animal.description:
We are reaching out because a special dog needs our rescue help. Elliott's mom was part of a hoarding situation over a year ago.  He was born in protective custody and is only one of a handful of pups that survived.  Elliott spent the first year of his life in a kennel and we are seeking a foster home and/or a forever family in order to remove him from the shelter. 
The caring staff at the shelter has been working with Elliot.  He is already almost walking on leash and is doing really well hanging out in the Placement Coordinator's office. He is very goofy, food motivated, seems very interested in meeting other dogs, and loves rope toys. Still a little shy with humans and will flinch away if approached too quickly, but he is showing interest and play bowing when excited. 
Please go to our website at www.dobermanrescuenm.org and complete an application to help this sweet boy grow up into an awesome Doberman!

Homer is one of our hospice dogs. He has been having some anxiety issues so he is now on some anxiety medication and his bloodwork indicates he may have Cushings, so further tests are needed. 

Homer was found as a stray and taken to an open intake shelter and not reclaimed by his owner. He is a 13-year-old schnauzer and about 4 years ago, he ate a chicken bone, and had bowel surgery so he has frequent bowel movements, including diarhea. 

Please consider SPONSORING Homer to help with his medical needs. You can click on the "Sponsor" button or Donations can be made to our Paypal at petprofilerescue@gmail.com or https://paypal.me/petprofilerescue to help with Ram's medical care.

Our senior dogs could use the fish oil, Chlorehexidine mousse for skin issues, Cosequin for joint issues, and Denamarin for liver issues. Our rescue dogs' Amazon Wishlist is here: https://www.amazon.com/hz/wishlist/ls/1PIG0Y2YAZ2MP…

We require an adoption application, phone interview, virtual house check, and meet and greet with your entire family. Send us an email at petprofilerescue@gmail.com for a for an adoption application or apply online at: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1S5v9x1oGSYLBSfheZJ_zSvkIHoT3Fe_xnsq5V75IX9w/edit?fbclid=IwAR0rU1zQezgZhhC_01_JpMFhujOq40cu8Xl4xKdiZ0b1L-3Pwm1Et-XI3K4

animal.description:
ADOPT ME ONLINE: https://ophrescue.org/dogs/9132

Mia is brimming with personality and overflowing with devotion. She is VERY active - ready to be your running buddy or your hiking pal. This little energizer bunny never runs out of go. She is believed to be 2-3 years old and currently weighs about 45 lbs. Everyone who meets her comments that she is much smaller than she looks in pictures. She's a solid 45 pounds, but not a big 45 pounds.

Mia is very smart, trainable, and treat-motivated. She has mastered basic obedience (sit, down, stay) and learned to ring the bells on the foster's doors to let them know she needs to go out. She quickly learned how to use a doggy door and is very respectful of the fence and baby gates. Mia is doing great with leash manners and would likely love the challenge of agility or more training.

Mia loves chew toys and rope toys and anything that squeaks, plus is happy to play fetch or tug, but she's equally happy to snuggle with you on the couch.

Mia gets very excited when she sees new people and recently gave a visiting plumber a tongue bath while he worked. She understands that four-feet-on-the-floor gets her more attention, but sometimes she can't help herself. She is housebroken and crate trained in her foster home. Mia needs plenty of exercise and should not be in a home with cats because she loves to chase small animals. 

This sweet girl is ready to find her forever family - she has so much love and devotion to give! To see more pictures and stories of Mama Mia, visit her foster mom's blog, www.AnotherGoodDog.org.

Click here and here to see her in foster care! 

To adopt this dog, or any OPH dog, fill out the simple online application at https://ophrescue.org 
Operation Paws for Homes, Inc. (OPH) rescues dogs of all breeds and ages from high-kill shelters in NC, VA, MD, and SC, reducing the numbers being euthanized. With limited resources, the shelters are forced to put down 50-90% of the animals that come in the front door. OPH provides pet adoption services to families located in VA, DC, MD, PA and neighboring states. OPH is a 501(c)(3) organization and is 100% donor funded. OPH does not operate a shelter or have a physical location. We rely on foster families who open their homes to give love and attention to each dog before finding a forever home.

Sage is a 2-year-old, 36 lb. hound mix girl. Sage is looking for a warm, soft bed or chair to sleep her days away on. She’s had a hard life thus far, fending for herself in the woods and raising her litter of 10 puppies before she was taken into rescue—she’s a tired momma! Sage is housebroken, loves her crate, scratches and will dance for her dinner! She has decided the indoor life is for her! Sage is timid of new people and things, and she will need time to warm up to you and patience when introducing new things. She is able to take very short walks on a leash. Sage is wonderful with other dogs, and ignores the foster family’s rabbit in his cage. She takes a treat so very gently! Sage has not been tested around cats or young children. A home with adults and children who are calmer would be the best fit for her (other dogs would be great too!). Can you give this sweet girl her forever home?

Please visit halfwaythererescue@gmail.com for information on meeting and/or adopting Sage!

animal.description:
Unique beauty Helen is special for many reasons. A one year old catahoula mix, she is what is called a “double merle”. This condition is responsible for her gorgeous coat and icy blue eyes, and as a result of it she is 100% deaf. A dog’s sense of hearing is very important, and without it Helen has naturally developed some defensive behaviors. Wary at first of new people and dogs, she warms up into a superbly happy, playful and affectionate girl as soon as she feels safe. She:
•	Is 45 pounds
•	Is working on house training
•	Is good with other dogs, but will snap if startled by a dog that she doesn’t see approaching
•	Is not good for a home with children
•	Walks nicely in a harness
•	Is medium to high energy
Helen needs a very special home that can take it slow with her and is prepared for the challenge of training a dog unable to hear commands. So worth the effort though, she adores the people in her life and will pour love into her new family. She has fully won our hearts and given the chance will certainly capture yours!

Helen is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and heartworm negative. 

For more information about Helen or our shelter please call us at (830) 693-0569 or visit our website at highlandlakescaninerescue.org 

If you would like to schedule a meet and greet with Helen or any of our dogs, please fill out an application at highlandlakescaninerescue.org/application-for-adoption

animal.description:
Opal is a 5/6  year old 54 lb white dog  mix foster in Olympia, WA. We estimate ages based on what the vets tell us. Every dog sees a vet upon intake, when they are spayed/neutered and again for a health certificate just prior to coming to the NW. Usually at least two different vets (which is always good to get different opinions on the age of the dog etc)

 

Opal is part boxer or part bulldog or ? We do not know. She had a litter in TX and now is spayed. She is energetic, affectionate, and attentive. She likes walks and is house and crate trained. She is a great companion for an active family with a secure fence 

She is an indoor dog who enjoys car rides, dog bones and dog beds. She loves her humans' companionship indoors. She will require daily walks and some dog training as she still pulls toward passerbys in some circumstances.

She is attentive to her human companions, but is interested in other people and dogs on walks.

Opal is a 6 Year old 54 lb Bulldog Terrier mix. In foster in Olympia, WA
She is a semi energetic and affectionate gal who loves her humans only! She is crate trained and likes walks. She is a great companion for an active family with a secure 6 ft fence. Bulldog experience is required. She is an indoor dog. She likes walks, car rides, dog bones and dog beds. She loves her humans companionship indoors. She will require daily walks and some dog training. Will require 6 ft fence. No apartments, rentals or children under 12 years of age.

This is a posting for HHS (Helotes Humane Society). You can fill out and application below. Yes you must COPY and PASTE this application link.

https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/HTX/Exotic/Other

Important: If you are interested in this pup/dog, please fill out the application (link listed above). The rescue will contact you once the application is received. Although we strive to answer everyone, due to the high volume of inquiries we receive, we cannot guarantee a response to all emails. Filling out the application is the ONLY way and ensures a response from the rescue. In addition, while you are emailing us, if others apply, you lose out adopting the dog you chose. We have hundreds and hundreds of puppies/dogs available so there really is no need to apply anywhere else. However, if you are applying or have applied anywhere else, we do need to know that.

SHANYE'S FOSTERS is a group of foster parents in the Olympia/Tumwater area. We foster dogs for rescues and assist them in adopting/rehoming of their pups/dogs by listing on this site. Many dogs posted here are available to pre adopt NOW directly from the rescue. The only ones in foster in the NW specifically state that. We have very few fosters so most need to be pre adopted. All adoption fees go towards rescuing more dogs in need. No one receives a salary. Shayne's Fosters is not responsible for any experience you have with any dog you might see posted on this site. They are the property of the sponsoring rescue who will supply all medical supporting records which is given with each dog when adopted.

Our adoption fees cover all medical costs to make sure the pups are appropriately vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and spayed/ neutered. It also covers the cost of transportation from Texas and the necessary health certificate documentation. The fees also include a negative heart-worm test for any dogs over 6 months. Some dogs/pups have additional medical, including but not limited to FHO, ACL, hernias, dental, and a myriad of other vetting. If the adoption fees seem high (which never cover the true cost of rescue), we recommend fostering for a good rescue. Fostering ensures you incur no vet bills and no boarding fees. We are always in need of good fosters. We are all volunteers who donate our time and resources to help save as many dogs/pups as we possibly can.

Thank you for choosing to adopt a rescue pup/dog. Worldwide over 1/2 or 1 billion puppies/dogs are PTS yearly. thousands and thousand daily (yes entire litters, pregnant/nursing moms are PTS daily just in U.S. shelters. Yes even entire litters of puppies yes DAILY in many US shelters! We firmly believe there is NO breed other than rescue for all species. Thank you for being part of the village it takes to save these precious lives.

Randall was such a sweet, young gentleman who is the happiest boy who will shower you with kisses and always be happy to see you. Just under a year old, Randall is a fun, active pittie mix who loves his walks and playing with his ball but don't fear, he loves his naps as well - especially when they come with snuggles! When he is ready to chill he'll climb on the couch and cuddle close.

He's just happy to be included in whatever you're doing...wherever you are is where he wants to be!

Randall does love his chew toys as well and can't wait to have some of his very own in his furever home. He does well in both the car and crate and seems to already know to do his business outside, as he'll let you know he needs to go out by sitting at the door. He has proven to possess excellent leash manners as well! Randall loves children, and while he gets along just fine with other dogs he would be happy to be the only dog in your home. He is treat motivated, but also easily motivated by just attention and picked up on "sit" quickly.

Randall is a lovebug who would be a great addition to a lucky family!
This guy is ready to find his forever family and is sure to be the happiest dog on the block wherever he ends up!

animal.description:
Meet Murphy!! Doc Murphy but we just call him Murphy.

Murphy is believed to be about 8 to 10 years young. Really we don't know because when he was rescued 2 plus years ago, he was in horrific conditions. 

Murphy has been on more trial adoptions then any other dog. Only because with in 24 hours people feel they can't bond but you give him the time to adjust and learn his new floor plan surrounding and he's the best dog ever.  See, Murphy is fully retired. All he wants to do is make up for lost time, enjoy life to the fullest. He wants to sleep peacefully, eat all he can eat all the time, enjoy life pass by without worries or concerns or stressing about surviving. Murphy just wants to live a happy calm life. 

Murphy most likely was born with poor eye sight and with time has lost it completely. But that does not affect him! He just wants to eat, sleep, sunbath, watch..... in his case listen to the news or radio, enjoy his toys and simple daily walks and the occasional car rides, why not?!  His favorite dog beds are round dog beds. He loved to donut roll in them. He overheard retirement is the way too go so he's sticking with it. 

When Murphy arrived he was heartworm and lyme disease positive as well had very bad skin condition. All which could of been prevented if he was not neglected and sentenced to live chained up outdoors most of his life. Murphy is a chill dude. He enjoys companionship. He is an independent dog and if he has a need he can't solve on his own, he will speak up. He's not an early bird dog either. He is in great health now and living it up. He is also awesome with kids, and dogs too but due to his poor eye sight he's best as an only dog/pet in the home. Only because he was attacked by dogs in 2 separate occasions. Once on a pack walk by 2 stray dogs, another when he was on a trial adoption and the potential adopter thought the dog park was ok to visit....... ????. Like, how? Another dog in the dog park litterally attacked him for no reason. See, most dogs struggle when meeting a blind or deaf dog. And while Murphy is good with dogs it's just best he's an only pet and gets all the attention to himself. And yes his daily walks or 2 is a must for him. As well as a nice size fenced in yard. 

Did we already mention how Murphy loves kids? He's a superstar with them.

Training is an ongoing process that has to be worked on daily. New issues opportunities show up daily that have to be addressed and or rewarded. Continue training is a must.

Adoption application and processes information can be found on our website www.animalhousesanctuary.org or by emailing us at animalhousesanctuary@yahoo.com

Name your price adoption with a minimum of $150

Date: 1/15/21

animal.description:
My name is Zoey. I’m 13 years old and was surrendered when my owner passed away. I’m a petite, white IG with a laid-back vibe. My hobbies include eating kibble, doing laps around my foster house, napping under blankets, and of course looking cute. I would prefer a human with a house or apartment without too many steps, because I have no idea how they work. I mean, first you’re up there and now you’re down here?  Make up your mind, human. If you insist on steps, you can feel free to carry me. I’ll wait.

You should know I have glaucoma in one eye and an early-stage cataract in the other. This means I need an eye drop twice a day for my glaucoma, but I’m used to it, so it will only take you a couple seconds. I see well enough to get around, but sometimes bump into things until I get my bearings in a new house. I don’t hear anymore, so just give me hand signals if you need something. You don’t have to tell me it’s dinnertime. My sniffer works just fine. I just had a dental procedure and am down to five teeth, but don’t let it fool you: I love to eat!

I am mostly potty trained, both outdoors and indoors on puppy pads, but I have been known to have a few accidents. If you are patient with me and remind me it’s time to potty I shouldn’t have too many problems. I am used to sleeping in a crate at night for my own safety, so long as it has a cozy bed and I can wear my cute pajamas to keep warm. I have a sweet disposition and would be okay as an only dog or if you have another senior dog. I don’t think I would do well in a house with kids. My ideal human would be someone who is home a lot and likes to keep things low-key. We can snuggle, watch Netflix and of course eat!

Visit us on FB at: http://www.facebook.com/IGrescueVa. Also, please fill out an app, as they are processed in the order in which they are received: http://www.midatlanticiggyrescue.com. Zoey is property of IGRF.

animal.description:
Marty is a Chihuahua approx 4 years old and weighs about 11 pounds.. Marty was rescued from Maricopa County and has been with Tucson Cold Wet Noses for two years. Now you might ask why so long? Marty needed some fine tuning. He was fearful of people and other dogs and would not always be on his best behavior. To make Marty more comfortable we gave him time and training to build up his confidence and to work on some of his fears no matter how long that might take.
Marty has had two fosters since being with Tucson Cold Wet Noses. He does well with other dogs but does best in a small dog home. Marty's first foster mom (who broke her leg hense the move) said he was fearful of the bigger dogs in the home but did well with the small dogs.
Marty takes time to warm up to his human but once he feels comfortable will seek out affection on his terms. He likes to cuddle but has boundaries and again it does take a little time to fully accept you but it's well worth the wait Marty behaved well at the vets which we are so proud of. He is a dog in progress but what strides he has made. Marty would do well with No Children in the home, a home that as at least one other dog as he does follow their lead. To meet Marty please contact us at info@tucsoncoldwetnoses.com or you can fill out an application at tucsoncoldwetnoses.com.

*Applications to adopt: wwwTucsonColdWetNoses.com Home Visit / ID and Residence Verification is required. Compliance does not imply or guarantee adoption. Approval is the sole discretion of CWN representative(s).

animal.description:
Meet Sawyer!!
Sawyer is a tripod! We rescued him after he was dumped in a box by a dumpster. His leg was broken in 6 places. He had 5 surgeries to try and save it but ultimately he had to have it amputated. 

Despite the hell he went through in his long-lost past life, Sawyer is such a joyful and happy boy! He is estimated about 3 years old. He had medium energy but LOVES to run around, he loves to swim, loves tennis balls, loves car rides, he loves other dogs and he loves kids! He is truly the happiest dog! (and he makes a great running buddy!)

Sawyer is a great listener, does great off-leash, he is curious, funny and can occupy himself easily with a bone! 

Sawyer is excellent with kids, as you can see in the photos. We would recommend kids over 8 solely because how bounce and energetic he is around them!

If you are interested in adopting Sawyer, please apply at www.twotailzrescue.org!

It typically takes 1 to 2 weeks. We only have 3 people working adoptions, and we are receiving 25 to 30 apps a day and hundreds of calls and inquiries, which slows the process for everyone. Adoption fee is $300.

Meet our Mission 5. They were born around 12/04/2020. They got their 1st shot 01/12/2021 and will be getting fixed around 03/10/2021. They will be going to their new homes no later than 03/20/2021.

Meet Claire (Chocolate Milk). She came in 01/14/2021 weighing 6.8 pounds. We anticipate she will weigh between 40 and 50 pounds full grown. All the puppies are well socialized and will make great companions. These pups should live to be 12 to 14 years old. If you are over 60, you will need to have a backup plan in place in the event you become unable to care for pup.

Applications can be completed at www.adoggie4you.org. Please do not call to ask if the dog is available. It will stay posted until we have enough applications to find a match. Meet Chika (Snowy). She came in 01/14/2021 weighing 6.0 pounds. We anticipate she will weigh between 40 and 50 pounds full grown. All the puppies are well socialized and will make great companions. These pups should live to be 12 to 14 years old. If you are over 60, you will need to have a backup plan in place in the event you become unable to care for pup.

Hazel is a 2 1/2 month old cattle dog mix. She has been in foster care in Louisiana since he was 2-3 days of age. She will be joining us at AHR on January 30th, along with his siblings Tater and Mr. B.

Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Pumpkin is ready to go to a new home!Pumpkin came to us in early September and the same day had emergency surgery for pyometra (infection of the uterus) and was diagnosed with heartworm disease. Over the past few months, she has undergone treatment for heartworm and has been recovering in her foster home where her activity was limited. Pumpkin had a good health report this week and is now allowed to slowly resume normal activity. She will need to be tested again in September 2021 to be sure that she is still heartworm free.Her list of skills include 'sit, down, heel' and she's working on 'leave it'. She doesn't steal food from countertops, and has no interest in getting on furniture. Pumpkin does like cuddling on the floor with her humans. Squeaky toys, soft toys and big bones to chew on are some of her favorite things. Pumpkin prefers cool weather. She hangs out near the air conditioner in the summer, and loves, loves, loves the snow! A home with small children will not be considered due to her size and never having lived with little ones.Pumpkin is up to date with vaccines, spayed, microchipped, and on flea/tick/heartworm preventative. Will Pumpkin be YOUR new best friend. She will love you forever!IMPORTANT - PLEASE READ
Click here for the ADOPTION APPLICATION if you are interested in adopting this pet.
Applications are the first step in the adoption process. Please do not call or email simply to express interest. We are all volunteers and receiving your application saves us time and helps to determine the best match for both people and dogs.
We provide as much information as we currently have on each dog in their description. For questions on the adoption process, including fees, please review the Adoption page. If you have additional questions or are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application. Once we receive your application someone will be in touch to answer your questions. We do not arrange visits to meet dogs without an application. If you'd like to meet a variety of dogs without filling out an application please attend one of our events, listed under the events link.
Thank you! 1/16/21 9:35 PM

animal.description:
Sadie is a 6-year-old, 75 lb, Shepard mix looking for her forever family. She is UTD, spayed, chipped, housebroken, and walks well on a leash. Sadie is low energy and would love a family to cuddle and snuggle with. She is not good with dogs, good with cats, and not sure with kids. Sadie does have minor skin alleriges, however they are controlled through regular baths. Sadie does not prefer car rides, however she LOVES her comfy bed and her people. 

Sadie has to find her new forever home because her current guardian rescued her from being euthanized but had no intentions to keep her and asked for our assistance to find her a permanent home. 

Adoption requirements are as such:


	No other dogs 
	No kids under 12
	Dog experience 


Please note, Sadie is part of Happy Trails Animal Rescues rehoming program. She has not been tested or evaluated and the information gathered is from the current owners personal statements regarding health and temperament. The owner is subject to placement outside of our organization. We cannot guarantee availability.

animal.description:
Jamie here! I am estimated to be around a 1 year old pit bull mix and weight about 50 lbs. I have done well in my temporary foster home, I'm so so nice to the doggies I have met and very tolerant of my hyper foster brother! I have had no accidents in my foster home and I even sit by the door to let them know I need to go out! I am the BEST cuddler and wag my tail any time someone walks by. I do great with the 9 year old kid in my foster home and I love everyone, but a family with older kids would be best as I'm still a puppy and don't quite know my size. I can get excited on the leash when I see new friends, so I will need some continued guidance on walks. I know most basic commands and I even know how to shake! That one is my favorite as I already love to wave my paw at everyone to say hello. I haven't shown any interest in chewing things and can be trusted around the house. I need a family with a yard and active lifestyle that can include me in all their activities. I would also very much prefer to go to a home that has a playful doggie companion I can romp around with! I have the typical pitbull play style, so I would appreciate if my new doggie sibling enjoyed jumping and wrestling with me! I am spayed and current on rabies and DAPP vaccinations.

If you are interested in meeting me please complete an application at https://www.circle2rescue.com/dog-adoption-application/ The adoption fee of $250 includes spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip and dewormer.

Please note, Circle 2 Rescue cannot guarantee the breed, composition or ages of our dogs as we usually have limited history prior to them entering the rescue. We make every effort to ensure the dogs are healthy.

animal.description: Meet Cameron: Cameron is thought to be a Carolina Dog/Pit mix around 2 years old. Cameron was found as a stray in a high kill shelter and scheduled to be euthanized when we rescued him. Cameron's current foster learned he isn't to fond of small children or big dogs as both scared him. Cameron did get along with puppies and older children. Cameron became very sick and was rushed off to the emergency vet. Cameron spent 11 days there recovering from what they thought was sepsis most likely related to a severe kidney infection. Cameron was severely dehydrated, lethargic with no appetite and loosing weight. They think Cameton might have diabetes insipidous but will know more after some more testing scheduled on January 20th. Cameron is now home with his foster family again and recovering amazingly. Cameron is eating like a champ, playing with his toys like a puppy and has not showed any signs of aggression. Cameron loves to go on walks, enjoys his crate and is house trained. Cameron is learning what doggy life with a family that loves you is suppose to be like. Once Cameron is healthy and has been cleared by the vet he will start his heart worm treatment. While going through Heart Worm treatment. We are hoping to find a forever family that can provide him a loving and healing environment. Cameron would do great in a home with a fenced in yard (fence required), older childreh, no cats or large dogs. Cameron is a very sweet boy who only wants to be loved and spoiled. If you are interested in adopting or meeting Cameron please go to our website at Charliescrusaders.org and fill out our adoption application.

animal.description:
My name is Red, and I am 6 years old. I am a very easy going and sweet boy. I am a lover of people and being around them.  In my foster home I enjoy being in the garden and watching the birds and chickens on the other side of the fence. I also like sleeping on my garden cot in the sun. I’m not very fond of the rain. It makes my feet wet! I will go out to do my business, but after that I’m right back inside.    I would like to be in a monogamous relationship with my person in regards to other dogs. I do have other foster dog siblings where I am now, but I’ve never had a family of my very own, and I long to find a best friend and family who will just hang out with me, play with me and love me. I know several tricks like sit and stay in place, and I walk nicely on leash.  My foster mom says I am very smart and eager to please, so maybe you can teach me even more fun stuff. I may have been left alone for long periods in the past because I prefer not to stay home alone for long periods.  I’m okay for around 6 hours without problem, but if you are gone for long periods I worry you are never coming back and get anxious.  I have a nice low energy level and I like a calm environment, so if you are a bit of a couch potato, we might be a perfect match. I’d be happy to hang out with you on the sofa watching movies or sitting on the floor in the kitchen while you cook. I’ll clean anything up you drop on the floor. I am super easy once I learn my routine. My foster mom says I am a pleasure to be around, and I bond with people very fast.  I am a good boy and am hoping I get a family of my very own soon who will love me, play with me and give me the attention I so enjoy. In return you will get the most loyal and loving friend you ever had! Check out my pictures too, I’m pretty adorable!  If you want to know more about me or meet me in person please contact Martina Animal Rescue at: martinaanimalrescue@yahoo.com, irinad@english-russian.us or (510) 697-0072. 

Love, Red

Application, home check and adoption fee required.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Jupiter and even though I am a little unsure of things, I am still excited to meet you! I am very playful and I love playing with other dogs. I am about 4 yrs old and weigh 8 lbs.

I am definitely looking for a furry buddy/best friend. I need a home with another dog that likes to wrestle and play. My foster mom thinks a dog bigger than me would be best, since sometimes I get excited while playing, and a bigger dog’s ‘no’ means more than a small dog’s “no”. We haven’t had any problems playing too hard, and I am learning to be extra gentle, just for good manners. If you have a dog that likes to run and play outside, I would really like to join in the fun!

My foster mom has been working with me on my potty training and walking on a leash, but I still have some training to be done. I am learning so much, but it is taking me a while to learn how to be the best dog ever! It seems no one really cared for me before, but now I have a chance at having a family to love. I need someone who is patient and has the time to spend with me so I can continue learning, but it will pay off in a lifetime of love!!

If you think you and I would be a great match, please fill out an application.  My foster mom is just waiting to give you a call so she can tell you more about me.

Hi everyone I'm Penny and look out world cuz I am ready to find my forever home! I am the happiest little beagle you will ever meet. I am 7 years old but I have the soul of a pup. Why am I so happy you ask? Well let me tell you my whole story. I started out as an outside dog in a old stinky pen. No one really bothered to play with me or wanted to love me. They just wanted me to have puppies. Well they did not give me good medicine to keep me healthy and I caught the heart worm, nasty worm! But that's all old news now, Woooo Wooooo My Foster Mom and the wonderful folks at Because You Care have helped me get better, and I am free of those nasty old critters. It has taken a long time but I'm all healthy now! I am loved , and I play, and I am the happiest beagle in the whole wide world. Wooooo Wooooo! So... I'm smart and I'm house trained, and crate trained (but I love sleeping in a snuggly bed). I like other dogs, not so much with cats, they run and I just want to case, I just can't help myself. I love people! I love kisses and belly rubs, and treats and walks and naps. So if you are ready for the happiest pup in the world then look e up That's me Penny Beagle.

Penny's adoption fee is $200 which includes her spay, vaccinations (rabies, distemper, lepto), microchip, heartworm test and flea and heartworm prevention. Also, six weeks of obedience classes if you chose to do so.

The Courtesy Post below means we are offering our website as an additional outlet to help an owner find their dog a new home.  We are not a shelter, it doesn't mean we've met or evaluated the dog, it means we are trying to help this owner find a good, responsible and most of all a loving home.

Courtesy Post for Owner: 
Below is what was written or told to us:
Bella is a 4 1/2-year-old female hound mix. She is spayed and up-to-date on her shots. Bella weighs about 40 pounds.
We adopted her in 2017 and about a year ago she started fighting with our other female dog in the house.

She is currently on anxiety medication for her shaking and hiding before and during storms, fireworks and any loud noises.  The vet thought it would help with her behavior towards our other female dog.  She needs to be the only pet in the home.  She has not been around small children but I wouldn’t recommend it due to her anxiety.

Bella enjoys car rides, she does pretty well on a leash but I would recommend a harness. She loves to play with toys. 

It takes her a little bit to warm up to new people but when she does she is the sweetest thing. 

She loves to cuddle and sleep in bed with us.
