animal.description:
Meet Bella!

10-year-old Bella became a Frosted Faces

on January 13th

through our Final Wish program. Bella had recently been diagnosed with diabetes and was unwell. Her elderly owner, who has deeply loved and cared for Bella since she was a puppy, didn't feel that she could manage the care Bella needed and made the difficult decision to relinquish her to us. After taking Bella to our vet to be evaluated, we started her on insulin and are monitoring her blood sugar with a glucometer. She is doing great! Bella is eating with gusto and has gobs of energy for uppies and kisses. Bella is such a friendly and sweet girl, and it is very easy to give her the injections.

Bella lives in a Foster Home (with a veterinary student!) and is getting extra TLC as we monitor her blood sugar levels to ensure her diabetes is well managed. We've heard from her Foster Mom that Bella has settled right in! She shared, "Bella sure knows how to make herself right at home! She is the most cuddly pup on the planet! Here's what I've learned about Bella so far: She has the most manners! She will paw you when she wants attention and wait patiently until your ready for pets. She is so respectful of other dogs space! She definitely greets my chihuahua every morning or in passing but totally gives her her space. Bella loves to greet all house guests. She never makes a peep or barks when people enter my home. She will wiggle her tail and make way to their lap and cuddle. She is truly the most perfect dog on the planet. Her diabetes is SO manageable because she loves her food and doesn't mind her insulin shots. We have her on a prescription diabetic diet, and she LOOOVES it. She has been such a champ about receiving her insulin vaccines, doesn't even make a peep!"

If you have experience with diabetes or want to learn, don't shy away from being Bella's mom or dad! We ask that you would be open to communicating with her previous mom about how Bella is doing and maybe even visit! Please apply at
www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply/

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/20/21 KG

Junior is a darling Pit Bull mix! He’s 2 years old and he weighs 54 lbss.  Junior looks pretty serious in his photos— but he’s actually just staring down a treat!  He’s very playful and silly and goofy, but as soon as the treats came out, all playing stopped and all of his focus was on the treat!  

Obviously, he’s very food motivated (you do have to watch your fingers, though. He needs work on taking treats gently).  

Junior is good with other dogs and plays in play groups. 

He has been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartworms.  

Adoption hours at our shelter: Monday - Friday 9am-4pm, BY APPOINTMENT ONLY, and some weekend hours.  To make an appointment or for more information, please call us at 913-321-1445.  If you have a dog, you can also arrange to bring your dog with you to meet our dogs to see if it's a good match.

Our dogs have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, dewormed, microchipped and tested for heartworms (if 7 months or older).

Visit our Petfinder home page at http://kckac.petfinder.com for more info about adopting our pets.

Breed:  St Bernard/ Bernese Mountain Dog Mix
Age:  3 years
Weight: 90 lbs.
Good with dogs: Yes
Good with cats:  No
Good with kids:  Older due to size
Energy Level: med-high energy

Meet Brutus!  Brutus has been in the current shelter he resides in for one full year ?.  Just doing the time, but without any crime.  Or maybe he's just a star, patiently waiting to be discovered.  Well, we see you Brutus, and we can't wait to help you fulfil your full potential to play the roll you were born to play as someone's "good boy!"

You might be wondering what kind of special talent's this good boy possesses.  Well, he has more than one, but the one he likes to show off the most is.... Drum roll, please.... Wait for it..... You guessed it..... He loves to PLAY BALL!  Brutus could play fetch with a tennis ball for hours if you let him.  Which is great because Brutus is a boy who will who will thrive when given regular physical exercise and/or mental stimulation.   So if you want a loyal and loving companion that likes to be active outside and snuggle on the cough when you're done, look no further!  Just make sure your couch is big enough. 

If you would like more information on Brutus, please contact Rose at RoseC@doubledogrescue.org.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Glenn and I was rescued from a shelter in Martin County before coming to Big Dog Ranch & Rescue. My owner of just 3 months surrendered me because he felt that he did not have the ability to provide the proper conditions for me to live my best hound life. I love ALL people and have lived in harmony with both male and female dogs. I have also spent a lot of time with children and I play well with them. I am very friendly and playful, but tend to be more gentle and submissive. I shouldn't be placed in a home with cats, as they are not my favorite and may incite my very strong prey drive. I am known for my typical hound-like hunting skills with rabbits and squirrels. I like to go for car rides and play with rope/squeaky toys. I am also afraid of thunder and lightening. I would be a great fit for an experienced hound owner and would love to have a great big space to run around and explore. I would benefit from some further training, as I am not quite potty-trained yet.

animal.description:
Boo (aka BooBear) is a Labrador Retriever mix who is about 3 years old. 

Boo was found abandoned and tied to a fence. Other details about his past are unknown. When he first arrived at his foster his body stayed rigid and tense for some time. Boo has mostly likely never known kind hands. 

In the past month he has been in a foster home and has made STRIDES!! Boo is learning how to be a loved family pet and is learning rules of the house! He is house trained and crate trained and hasn’t displayed any separation anxieties. 

Boo has learned some basic commands like WAIT, and KENNEL. He does struggle with SIT, but it is believed that sitting somehow makes him feel vulnerable or uncomfortable. Even on his own, Boo chooses not to sit most of the time. He prefers to either stand or lay down. 

Boo walks great on a leash and only requires slight corrections most of the time. He gets along great with other dogs and is very playful! 

Boo would do well with another playful canine companion! Car rides do make Boo nervous, but he is getting more comfortable with them. Riding with a trusted companion seems to ease his nerved.

Boo loves to chew on his bones and other toys. He also loves to run and play outside! He requires exercise, whether it is playtime during the day or daily walks.

Boo is ready for a furever home!

animal.description:
Hi I am Maya. I am around 2 years old and around 10 lbs. I am a cairn/rat terrier mix we think. I am a calm, easy going love bug. I am a bit shy when we first meet however I soon become your best friend.  I love to run and play outside with my foster pup friends. I came into rescue with my 4 babies, I was a wonderful mother.  All have been adopted and now it's my turn. I need a home that will be patient with me as I learn the new routine.  I am a quiet soul that startles easy, whip smart and athletic (I can literally climb out of any enclosure....it's how I got a little peace from my kids) however I was never destructive when I got out of our play pen. 
My previous owner was careless and didn't have me on consistent heart worm prevention and I have tested mild positive for heart worms. I have no clinical symptoms and have already been started on treatment. 
Adoption fee is $225 it includes spay/neuter, annual vaccinations, rabies license, microchip, dewormer, heart worm preventative for the month, vet exam.  Please go like our Facebook page at  http://www.facebook.com/barkandroll .  Follow us on  instagram/twitter @barkandrollrc to see more pictures of me as well as other dogs in our rescue.  You can access an adoption application on our website http://www.barkandrollrescuecompanions.com  It usually take 1-2 days to complete the application process.

animal.description:
Meet Lola a gorgeous 1.5 year old American Staffordshire Terrier Mix (breed is just a guess) who weighs in at 65 lbs. Lola is a sweet girl who loves to go for walks, go on car rides and hang out with her humans. Lola is an expert at giving doggie kisses and snuggles. Lola is a happy and goofy girl who loves to play with her doggie toys, roll around in the grass and follow her foster mom wherever she goes. Lola would do best in a home where someone is at home a good portion of the day, even after COVID. Lola enjoys her daily walks, but seems to need the freedom of being off leash in a fenced-in backyard. Lola is a social girl and loves to meet people and other dogs. If there are kids in Lola's home, they should be 8 years and up as Lola is not in a foster home with children. Lola needs an adopter who has recent large dog experience. Lola is not suited to apartment/condo living. She is spayed, microchipped, up-to-date on vaccines, and preventatives and eager to find a family to love!

The adoption fee for this dog is $350 which includes routine vetting and spay/neuter.

***Please note that our first step is submitting an application (it does not commit you in any way but allows us to discuss with you if you and the dog are a good fit). In addition, an important step in approving adoption applicants is to complete a vet check. Vetting of current and past pets is very important to us, thus we will be speaking with the vet(s) listed on your application to ensure that your current and previous pet(s) are kept up to date on vaccines (including rabies), spayed or neutered, maintained on appropriate monthly preventatives and examined annually by your vet.***

If you would like to meet Lola, please fill out our online application by clicking HERE and then email Kim at KLarimerLovepaws@gmail.com

If you are viewing this on PetFinder or other venue, please go to our website at www.lovepawspg.org

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Beans, and I am a 9 year old loving girl.  My owner is losing our home, and I am sad because I will be losing both my family and my home. I am a 60 lb bundle of adorable love as you can see from my pictures. I prefer a monogamous relationship with my person without other dogs, animals or kids that I might have to share my person/s with. At my age I like to be queen of my castle. I love to cuddle and be right by your side. I love rubber toys, rope toys and getting my aerobic exercise chasing the laser pointer. I tire pretty quickly after that, so if you're a bit of a couch potato, I may be the perfect girl for you. I walk nicely on leash and am great at sit and stay. I would love a home with a backyard to play in. I'm a bit sensitive to some noises like thunder and fire alarms and get all shaky, but I'm easily comforted being swaddled in a blanket or being close to my person. I also feel safe in my crate. One of my favorite treats is peanut butter and salmon. Together is even better. Peanut butter in a Kong works too for a special treat. I'm in great health overall. I do have some allergies that are easily treated, I'm up to date on shots and all my vet records are available. My owner will provide my two beds, large crate, several toys, food bowls, leash, harness and muzzle. I'm very sad about losing my family, but am hopeful someone is looking for a loyal companion to experience life with that will give me the love I am losing. If you want to know more about me or meet me in person, please contact martinaanimalrescue@yahoo.com  Love, Beans

Application, home check and adoption fee required.

animal.description:
ROXIE - COURTESY POSTING

Roxie is a middle aged (7-9 year old) chihuahua mix that weighs in at 13 lbs. Roxie was among the 50 that were rescued alive from a hoarding situation in GA, of about 150 dogs. She is spayed now, but has been over bred in the past. 

Roxie faces a few challenges; she has exhibited some neurological damage, and her back end doesn’t work as well as it should. Her stride wobbles in the rear and she has a tendency to slide her back feet on the floor. She has occasional accidents that she doesn’t know is happening. She has less feeling back there and tends to bite her feet. 

She doesn’t appear to like other dogs, and would enjoy being an only dog. We have not observed her with other pets so we can’t speak to her inter-specie behavior. 

Roxie is a very sweet and very loving girl, she is a true lap dog. Her favorite toys are squeaky toys that she will squeak until they stop. Roxie doesn’t bark a lot, but she does have an adorable snore. 

She is crate trained. Roxie would perfectly fit in a home with lots of patience, love and attention. She is truly a delightful girl. 

She is spayed, UTD on shots, HW neg and on HW prevention.Her adoption donation is $250.00.

If you are interested in the above dog, please do not email us and tell us that you are interested, but submit an adoption application. The link for the application is below.

To submit an application go here……chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application/An application must be submitted and approved before a meet-n-greet can be scheduled.

Your current dogs/cats must be spayed or neutered unless a veterinarian has determined that your current pet(s) should not be fixed due to medical reasons. 

They must also be up-to-date on shots and on HW preventative.Reference checks and a home visit are required so SE dogs can only be adopted in NC/SC, VA, TN, AL, MD and GA.

animal.description:
Meet Hazel! This pretty bully girl with snow white coat and adorable markings was found running as a stray in rural SC. Animal control was notified, and no one came looking for her. She was not spayed or microchipped and is still a very young pup. She has pretty good social skills and was heartworm negative on intake, so we believe she'd been living inside a home as part of a family.

Hazel has been in her SC foster home almost a week now, and is being fostered in a home with 4 other large dogs. She does great as part of the pack and loves to play. She was introduced first to the most selective dog in the home, Clarysse, who took to Hazel right away, and they were instant buddies. If Clarysse approves of you, the rest of the pack does too.

While Hazel was a little timid at first after coming into a new home, she quickly settled in. She is crate trained, housetrained, and has a medium energy level. She loves stuffed critters, loves to play, and really enjoys the company of other dogs. While she's good with people, Hazel would rather be playing with a dog, so having a dog playmate in her next home is a priority.

Her foster mom describes her as very sweet and puppyish in her ways. She's working on her leash walking skills in her foster home and learning basic commands. We think Hazel will make a great family dog and pup companion. She will be making her way to N. VA in early February.

More updates to follow as we learn more about this adorable, fun pup.

***Preference will be given to homes with another young playful pup, and some large dog or bully breed experience***

BREED ESTIMATE: AmStaff/Pointer mix
GENDER: Female
APPROXIMATE WEIGHT: 48 lbs
APPROXIMATE AGE: ~ 1 year old
COAT TYPE: Short
ADOPTION FEE: $400
OTHER INFO: utd on shots/spayed/microchipped/
LOCATION: Rock Hill, SC

FOR MORE INFO OR TO ADOPT: Please go to https://adopt.worthydog.org and complete the application.

You can also help save dogs like this one by becoming a foster, providing a rescue dog with a temporary home and giving them the love and care they need until they are permanently adopted. Every person who fosters is directly responsible for saving the life of a dog, because we can only save as many dogs as we have foster families available to welcome them into their homes. If you think you might be interested in becoming a foster and want to learn more, please go to https://foster.worthydog.org and fill out an application.

Worthy Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue that primarily adopts to families in the DC Metro area.

animal.description:
Meet Cider!

7-year-old Cider entered Animal Friends of the Valley as a stray and became a much-loved favorite of their staff and volunteers. When we picked him up on January 14th, they stood outside to see him off. Cider is that kind of boy! He is great with cats, dogs of all sizes, and kids, too!

We exited Cider knowing he had what looked like a handful of mast cell tumors on the back of his leg, but the whole inside of his thigh is also thick tumorous metastasis. We discussed many surgical options with our wonderful vet, Dr. Savides at College Animal Hospital and what is best for Cider and his quality of life. We decided on the only really viable option - removing the ulcerated mass on his leg to alleviate the discomfort and risk of infection.

Cider is the sweetest, best boy! T

hankfully, he is living in a foster home and getting lots of TLC following surgery, but we still want to find Cider a family of his own for the rest of his days.

Might that be you? Please apply at: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply/

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/27/21 KG

animal.description:
Special needs
Rosie is a sweetheart miniature poodle. She is only four, but she has epilepsy, and thus she needs someone who can care for her in special ways. She is beautiful with a heart-shaped nose. Rosie loves walks and being close with her people. She is a friendly, playful dog, and she gets along well with everyone. She is not timid or afraid of new people or situations. Rosie is generally quiet at home and enjoys naps on the couch. She has to be let out every 2-3 hours due to a frequent need to do her jobs, so she would do best with a family who could provide her with regular access to a safe, fenced-in yard, but she is not an outdoor dog. Rosie is more of a lap dog. Rosie is a good companion even though the anti-seizure medications have caused her to be less lively and interactive than before. She has been taking medication for almost 2 years now. Another side-effect of the medication is that Rosie is always hungry, so her diet needs to be well managed too. Rosie is 16 lbs. The main challenge is that Rosie continues to experience seizure episodes at times, and when this happens, on her worst days, she becomes disoriented, unaware of who her family is, and unable to control her own body functions. Currently, Rosie gets 32.5 mg of phenobarbital twice a day. The medication lessens the seizure frequency, intensity, and duration, but the seizures still occur. A new owner needs to be able to handle this and be aware that the episodes sometimes occur at night, and that Rosie occasionally may get up at night and need to go out to urinate. Fortunately, Rosie has more good days than bad days, but she needs a family that can care for her with compassion, health awareness, and schedule flexibility. Rosie is easy to love and hopes to find a family that can make her life happy and comfortable. Coat: Medium-length, white, curly, non-shedding, hypo-allergenic. House-trained: Yes, but prone to accidents – needs frequent opportunities to go out. Health: Has special needs to monitor medications and diet due to seizure episodes. Good in a home with: Other dogs and children. Not used to cats. Birthdate: 10/2016

animal.description:
Hanni is a very bright and interesting pup, who loves to be petted, and gives you a lot of love in return.  

He is a very loyal boy, whose previous life is unknown to us, as he had to be trapped when he was first found in the neighborhood near a high kill shelter. 

Hanni isn’t sure what to make of small children yet. Possible that some were rough with him  or/and maybe some background of punishment in there. 
But he would do best with older kids, 14 and above, who have experience with large breed dogs. 

New faces take him a few minutes to accept into foster home. When he mouths he plays well, never broke skin or fabric. He has a noticeably clean teeth and gums. For a large doge he doesn’t carry much of a scent. 

His first night was anxious, needing lots of attention until around 9pm, he sleeps exceptionally well alone in a padded open crate with the door open, not afraid of kennels. 
Hanni prefers his spot very close to humans most the time, and finding dry spots to sunbathe on. He can sleep several hours undisturbed. He likes dog parks, and he knows a few tricks like sit, lay down, come, & had no accidents in the house. He’s non aggressive with food.

He has done good when tested with cats, however his foster home does not have cats, so introductions need to be slow and patient. 

Hanni is about 18 months old, neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. He is kept on heartworm and flea preventatives.  

His adoption fee includes his cost of transport from Texas to any out of state adopter. 

To meet this sweet boy via facetime or in person, please send an application via www.savesomesouls.com

She seems to do fine around the small dogs in our care. When it comes to the big dogs though, she is not a fan. Not good with cats either. Bella is a great walker and will listen to your commands. Experienced dog owners are encouraged for her. Her company will be more than reward for the extra guidance she will need.

We know there are some 3rd party websites giving mis-information on the location of the pet you may be interested in. For correct information, please visit the location of the animal's name listed directly after their name, and visit the bio for more information. Thank you!! (Ex: "Sparky - Chino Hills Location will mean you go to Chino Hills; "Fluffy - Claremont Location will mean you go to Claremont; and "Fido - Costa Mesa Location will mean you go to Costa Mesa) There may also be mis-information about the status of an available pet. Tony is a gorgeous Husky boy who came into a rural shelter as a stray but has been rescued by 11th Hour. He is about 2 years old, weighing about 65 pounds and has 2 different colored eyes!!.

Tony is a super sweet guy who is friendly with other dogs, but is a no go for cats. We don't think he has ever lived with kids, so older ones who have dog experience would be best. He also needs a lot of training and structure, something he has missed out on in his life. Tony has a lot of energy but walks pretty well on a leash. He would really like to have a fenced-in yard because he likes to go, go, go, but anything under 6ft won't keep him in. Huskies are an active breed who need plenty of exercise, and breed experience is preferred.

If you are interested in Tony, please fill out an application at www.ehrdogs.org and be sure to ask for him by name, TONY SCAS!

animal.description:
New kid on the block Lucy is a gorgeous one year old Husky/Shepherd mix. About 50 pounds right now and is spayed.
As is typical with a young Husky, she is very high energy and needs an active household with no small children. Teenagers would be a good age for her.  Lucy needs a 6 foot fully fenced yard and LOTS of exercise. Applicants with Husky experience or first hand knowledge of similar breeds will be prioritized.

We also think Lucy would benefit from another active dog in the household if we can find the right fit through the meet and greet process. She can be dog reactive so we will likely need more than one meetup to be sure if will work out. We have not cat tested Lucy but we suspect she will not be a good fit with them.

If you have the experience described, you can meet Lucy on Saturdays from 10-2 at 809 Rockford Rd SW.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.To speed up the adoption process, please complete our Pre-Adoption Application.I love everyone! I play very well with other dogs and am great with kids!Prior to adoption I will be altered, vaccinated, health checked, dewormed, and micro-chipped.
Adoption Fee $500 +taxes/feesIf you would like to meet me please fill out a pre-adoption application at www.tailsrescue.orgHappy Tails Adoption Center is open on Sundays from 12-5pm. We are located at 7940 University Ave NE, Fridley. Dogs are at events based on the availability of their foster family. Please fill out a pre-adoption application so we know you are interested in meeting/adopting one of our animals.The breeds of our dogs and cats are a 'best guess.' We often do not know what mix they are and have to base it on what we think they look like, and base it on breeds often found in the area they came from. Most of our dogs who have gotten DNA tests done are 4-10 breeds mixed together. Because their breed mix is a guess we cannot guarantee a 'full grown size' of many of our younger animals.Interested in adopting me? Click here to fill out an application!Happy Tails Rescue Minnesota is located at 7940 University Ave NE, Fridley MN 55432. We are open for adoption events from 12-5 every Sunday. If there is a certain animal you want to meet at one the events please fill out a preadoption application to directly contact their foster family or check our Facebook page to see if they will be there! Their event attendance is based on the availability of their foster family.
Home visits (video tours or in person) are required for all dog adoptions. All of our cats and dogs are INDOOR pets and are NOT to be left outside unattended (even in a fenced yard), or running loose!

animal.description:
Location Valley Center, CA
(If this ad is running the dog Is available!)
Denali is the happiest and one good looking husky boy who has endured a life of neglect. 
We picked him up from a high kill shelter in the most Deplorable condition. His fur was receding, he was disoriented and not eating. Several tests revealed Cushing’ disease. He went on a treatment as he started to feel better day after day. He now has a great appetite, is very active and never stops smiling. He does have to take his daily meds which we cut to a minimal as he is showing good progress. 
Denali is about 5-6yo, neutered male. He Loves his walks/ runs and lounge outdoors. He has no problems with other dogs. (Cats unknown.) 
He is very active to say the least, and is full of life. We are looking for a caring family for him who could take him in to continue his daily regiment and help this boy to have a life he never knew. 
Affection is new to him, he is submissive and loves his hugs. 
Saving this sweet boy was the most rewarding experience. And we are hoping he can now transition to a private residence living to continue his new journey in life. 
His new fur is growing out slowly but surely, although still lots of patches of missing fur. 
He would do best in a home with a decent yard as he Loves to lounge outdoors but is always eager to come inside and sleep on his soft blankets. He would also do best with someone who has time to spend with him and is experienced with special needs pets. 
We are hopeful that a kind family is out there to take over what we have started to turn his life around. 
————
If you are interested in Denali please respond with detailed information about your home and family starting with location, age, other pets, other occupants and ages, yard and fencing. 
(No apartments please.) 
Thank you.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Lulu (SC) is a female Pit Bull Terrier mix rescued in South Carolina. Our veterinary partner estimates that Lulu is 1.5 years old at the time of intake in January 2021. Lulu is good with people and other dogs. Lulu is a beautiful girl who deserves way more than the life she has had thus far. We found Lulu in a kill shelter in a devastatingly emaciated condition. To make matters worse, Lulu was trying to care for a litter of puppies while she herself was starving. One by one her puppies passed away until she only had 4 left. That's when Rescue Dogs Rock NYC stepped in and quickly scooped Lulu and her pups out of that shelter and brought them to our veterinary partner where Lulu is receiving all of the medical care she requires. Lulu is amazing sweet, but understandably a bit scared at the life she has experienced. That life is over, and Lulu now needs a forever family who can show her how happy life can be. If you can replace Lulu's sad memories with fantastic memories, please apply online to adopt Lulu (SC) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

Koda has lived with children previously, but a home with older children would be best since he does tend to jump up sometimes and can knock over little ones. If interested in Koda, please email the canine department at Jrein@carrollcountymd.gov to request an application for adoption be sent to you which is required. Charlie came to us from another rescue, as he was an owner surrender. Charlies dad had gone into assisted living and could no longer keep him. No one in the family was able to keep him.

He hasn't had an accident in his kennel and appears that he is housebroken. But he did mark once or twice while in the office (there are lots of smells here). He approached everyone with a wagging tail and was excited to be out of the kennel. He even said hi to a little girl and licked her hands and face.

Meet Cooper. Cooper is an 8-year-old, male hound mix.  He weighs about sixty pounds. Cooper is good with dogs and children ages ten and older. He has a high prey instinct and therefore is not good with cats. He will make a great family dog; he is housebroken, knows his basic commands (sit, lie down, stay, and give paw) when motivated with treats. Cooper is sweet and calm with a low to moderate activity level. He enjoys walks but will pull hard if he sees a cat, squirrel, deer, etc. He would love to have a home with a fenced back yard to explore. Cooper has been fully vetted, is neutered, and is up to date on his vaccinations. To adopt Cooper please visit our website www.peace4paws.org and fill out an adoption application.


Dog Size Guidelines:
Small: 25 lbs and under (11 kg)
Medium: 26–60 lbs (12 – 27 kg)
Large: 61–100 lbs (28 – 45 kg)
Extra Large: 101 lbs or more (46 kg)

Coco came in to us pretty scared and wasn't sure about us at first. In her previous home she would get beaten up by the other dogs in the household so she may be more timid around other dogs. When we tested her with other dogs she just seemed scared but did okay with the other dogs. If you have other dogs we do ask you to bring them to meet her to make sure they get along before adopting. 

Coco is one of the sweetest dogs you'll meet! She has come a long way since being here at the shelter where at first she didn't even want us touching her. Now that's all she wants! She loves to be with you and will come over to lay in your lap with you. She loves affection and loves giving you kisses! She is laid back for the most part and wouldn't mind just snuggling up with you. She is also housebroken and will try to wait to go potty outside. 

Coco is a 1.5-year-old female Labrador Retriever mix that weighs 57 pounds. She will be spayed and microchipped before going home and will stay at the shelter until she is spayed. She is current on her vaccinations, flea, and parasite prevention.

animal.description:
Willow is a precious puppy who is a part of a litter of 5 who were all saved from a local kill shelter. Currently weighing 35 pounds, her estimated date of birth is August 20, 2020. This pup has a gorgeous, soft black coat with tons of white on her chin, chest and belly and even a little white stripe down her face! Willow is perfectly crate trained and sleeps on an extra large orthopedic bed. If given the opportunity, Willow would house train VERY quickly given that she is so wonderful about her potty schedule. Friendly & sweet, Willow loves everyone she meets. She is used to being crated at night and playing in a safe, fenced yard during the day with other pups. Willow is awesome with other dogs and will be fine with cats and other animals if introduced as a puppy. Eager to please, Willow is smart. She learns quickly and, although she has only been worked with a handful of times, she already knows come, sit, down, over and is learning paw. Willow is now healthy, fully vetted and ready for her forever home. Her wish list consists of an inside forever home with a big fenced yard for playtime, a home with lots of toys and another doggy friend for play time and pet parents who understand the time commitment that a puppy requires. Adopters who are retired or work-from-home parents are ideal as they have the time to spend with the pet. Adopters committed to doing a 6 week basic obedience class to ensure Willow's continued success at being a good canine citizen would also a plus (and to ensure the new puppy parent's education level). If you think you have the perfect home for Willow, contact us at info.caresga@gmail.com for an adoption application. We adopt up north and all over so please ask for details. $400 adoption fee and a vet reference is required to ensure a great home (this means you have had a pet so we can call to verify their level of care). Eligibility for adoption means your current or past pets are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccines and on monthly heartworm and flea prevention. Please be aware that we do not allow shock collars (ie underground fences) or "pens" as an alternative for a fenced yard.

We do our best to place our rescue pets in the very best homes. Please be aware that we have an application which also includes required vet records showing your existing pets are current on preventative medical care. Puppy adopters please take note that we generally try to place our puppies into homes where at least one parent is retired/stay at home/works from home to ensure the puppy gets enough attention and training (puppies cannot hold it all day in a crate) so please have a plan ready when contacting us. For safety reasons, we try not to place small dogs or puppies in families with children under 5 (there may be exceptions depending on situation).

Typical adoption fees for puppies are $350, juvenile dogs $300, adults dogs are $250, senior dogs are $150. Some pets, smaller dogs for example, may have a higher than normal adoption fee but we will alert you if there is a variance. Dogs rescued from China always have a higher adoption fee. Adoption fees help our group offset PART of the cost of rescuing, rehabilitating, and getting the pet healthy so they can go on to find a loving home with someone willing to give them a second chance at life. This amount includes each animal being current on age appropriate vaccinations including DHPPL, bordetella, influenza, rabies, and boosters when appropriate. De-wormed for any internal parasites (round worms, hook worms, tape worms and whipworms) with Drontal Plus, 4DX tested heart-worm negative (if positive, they are treated), tested negative for tick borne diseases, spayed/neutered, implanted with a micro-chip and have been examined by a veterinarian to certify that they are healthy. Any other known health issues are treated as well prior to adoption (examples: UTI, broken bones, contagious infections, dental cleanings, etc). All animals are also on a regime of flea and heartworm medication every month. Lifetime registration for the micro-chip is included in each adoption fee. In addition, each adopter will go home with a fitted collar, tags, a bag of dog food the pet has been on, copies of all vet history, and an adoption kit filled with valuable information and coupons as well as other various treats or toys as promotions become available. All puppy adoptions include two puppy training books, the Puppy Primer & Way To Go by Patricia McConnell, and all adult adoptions go home with Love Has No Age Limit by Patricia McConnell to help ensure a smooth transition for your new family member.

We ask that you consider an additional donation on top of this pet's adoption fee. This money will go directly into our Adoption Fund to be used exclusively for rescuing and caring for other pets in need. Many pets we take in have very high vet bills to get them healthy and adoptable for the public - much higher than their adoption fees. We receive no government funding and rely solely on donations from our community and caring adopters to continue our rescue efforts!

animal.description:
Roscoe was transferred to THS from another shelter, and is now looking for a new home! Roscoe is an active and happy guy that has that glass-half-full personality! Everyone is a friend to this social guy, and he loves to snuggle! He is also social and playful with other dogs that he has met on-leash at the shelter. He also enjoys car rides! Roscoe can sometimes be a little nervous in new places initially, but quickly settles in once he's comfortable. Roscoe can be excitable initially, and would benefit from some basic obedience including loose-leash walking and to help boost his confidence. 

Roscoe was recently treated for heartworm, and will need restricted activity (no running, jumping, rough play) for 8 weeks following his treatment. It will also be important that he remain on monthly heartworm preventative - his new family will be asked to purchase a 1 year supply of heartworm preventative (at a discount) at the time of the adoption, in addition to his adoption fee. 

Please follow this link to learn more about our current adoption process: https://toledohumane.org/covid-19-update

animal.description:
Champ is very outgoing.  He is always playing.  He doesn’t care who he plays with, us or our foster family.  He’s a funny guy too because he likes to do goofy things like run around the backyard with a toy that is as big as he is.

Champ got his name because he was very sick when we came to the rescue.  Actually, we were all quite emaciated and our little bellies were full of worms.  Champ had it worse than the rest of us.  He didn’t want to eat or drink.  Our foster mom made him.  She would hold him and tell him that he needed to fight like a champ to get better.  And, boy, did he!  He is bigger than most of us now. 


"C" Puppies bio: 

Hi everyone! 
We are the “C” puppies because all of our names begin with the letter “C”.  Our names are Carol, Clara, Charlie, Chester, and Champ.  We are about 12 to 14 weeks old.  Sorry, but we don’t remember exactly when we were born nor do we remember what breeds our mom and dad are.  Our foster mom says that we are beautiful puppies.  Is beautiful a breed?  We may look a lot alike, but our personalities are very different.  
Onto the boring stuff. We have all been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, and microchipped.  However, we will need another set of puppy vaccinations when we’re a tad bit older.  The vet said that we are ready to find our forever homes!  We all currently weigh between 13 and 16 pounds.
So, if you are looking for a friendly, sweet puppy and you think one of us would make a good addition to your family please let the people at Toledo’s Pet Bull Project know by going to www.toledospetbullproject.com and filling out an application.  There is no cost and no obligation to fill out an application.  However, there is a small adoption fee of $225 to help cover the cost of our vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter, etc.  There is also an additional $50 training fee that is refundable when you take us to a puppy training class.

We hope to meet you soon!

Please contact Cindy Robinson (cindyrobinson@hswctn.org) for more information about this pet.All HSWC animals are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and up-to-date on vaccinations before adoption (if species appropriate).
Application and counseling is required prior to all adoptions.

Individuals interested in adopting a puppy are STRONGLY encouraged to download and read this FREE ebook. Even if you've raised puppies in the past, this is an invaluable resource to help make your new addition successful!

Maize came into our care very pregnant. She gave birth to 11 puppies, who have all found homes. Maize was a wonderful Mom. It is her turn to find her furever home.

Maize's foster mom has this to say about her. Maize is very good at sitting and posing for pictures! She will also lay down, and go to her bed for a treat. Maize is still working on her signal to go outside, but when taken outside she knows what to do. Maize does great in a gated area if needed. She isn't crazy about staying in a crate. Maize is very affectionate, and will be a great cuddle buddy for anyone who needs someone to watch Netflix with. Her favorite games are fetch and tug of war. She is very good with new people if introduced slowly. Treats are always helpful. Maize is unsure of new dogs and would probably do better as an only gal. However, with proper introductions I believe Maize could make some new canine friends over time. Maize is currently being treated for heartworms. The Humane Society will continue to provide this treatment in an adoptive home. Contact maryjames@hswctn.org for more information.

animal.description:
Dixie’s Story , Submit an application and send me a message on Face Book so we can see if your match. https://www.peytonssafehaven.org/adoption-application

Dixie was found on the back roads of East Texas. She was pretty malnourished, a little skittish and in heat when we found her. After posting on several lost and found pet pages, no owner came forward. 

Dixie was pretty cut up around the face and neck when we picked her up. Our vet confirmed her wounds were probably due to a dog fight. He also aged her at 1-1.5 yrs of age and said she may have had a litter of pups already. Our guess is she is part American Bulldog and Pit mix.

Dixie is super playful and loves attention. This girl is all muscle. She weighed in at 72 lbs when we took her for a well checkup and spay. Her ribs were still showing. She has since filled out and looks amazing. She seems to love guys!

Dixie has become quite loyal in just the couple months we have had her. We have learned that she prefers to be center of attention and prefers not to share that love, however, she is warming up to our dogs with supervision. We walk her multiple times daily on a leash and she is perfectly fine with our pack walking along with us and she has started playing with them through the fence.

Dixie loves her pool when we get back from walks and is extremely smart. She seems to always be smiling and just wants to please. She has learned to sit and lay down on command. She is doing pretty good with the “stay” command until we release her. It’s a work in progress along with the no jumping part. Jumping comes from excitement. She thinks she weighs 5 lbs but reality is, she is closer to 90 now.

Dixie is a beautiful dog with her brindle markings and muscular physique. I really believe she would make someone an amazing dog and I think she would be fine with OLDER kids. I would not recommend young children or elderly because she is so big and powerful. A high energy family or single person would be great! Maybe a one dog household would work best so she doesn’t feel she needs to compete for that love. With time and training, she may learn to be part of a pack.

All in all, Dixie is a beautiful, healthy, happy girl. I know there is a forever home out there somewhere for her! See Less

Butters is a sweet, young guy who spent some time in PACC's decompression program for shy pups and is now feeling much more confident. Butters came to PACC by way of a friendly animal protection officer. While the weather is starting to become quite nice, Butters decided he'd had enough of the outdoor life and decided to hitch a ride to PACC so we can help set him up with a family of his own. Butters is a social pup who has been charming staffers and volunteers alike since he arrived at PACC shortly before Christmas. In play group, Butters was so excited to meet the other dogs he started greeting them through the fence. By the time he got into the yard, he was all waggy tail and tried to engage in a little bit of play (he doesn't really know how, and would love an owner that can show him the ropes.) Butters is a sweet dog who would do best with a confident owner or owners who can help him feel comfortable in his new home. If Butters sounds like your type of pup, make an appointment to meet him today.

animal.description: Meet Rocky, owner of quite possibly the bestest and most adorable underbite in all of Pima County. Rocky lived with the same family for his whole life and then found himself in a new home through no fault of his own. Things didn't work out there for Rocky so sadly he ended up at Hotel del PACC and he's hoping for a short stay. His previous family said that Rocky lived inside and was housebroken. He did well with a dog companion his size and with children ages 7-10. In his dog eval it took him a little time to warm up but he did eventually greet the other dogs and engage in play. He even tried to play with the humans. Volunteers say that Rocky loves him some treats, is enthusiastic about getting out for his walks and he enjoys being pet and loved on. He's the perfect age to bring into a new home - a courteous gentleman, no puppy shenanigans and he cleans up after himself and won't drink the last cup of coffee without making a new pot. If you are looking for a guy who will make you smile with his goofy grin Rocky just may be your guy.

animal.description:
Please read entire description. Jack's adoption fee is $100. He needs a home with a securely fenced yard and no other pets. If interested, please apply at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting.  

Jack is a small, 20 pound, 10 year old, mixed breed boy looking for a new home. His hair is wire-y and he has some features like a Chihuahua but a docked little tail almost like a Pug. He loves everyone he meets. Jack enjoys visiting company and was always good when the caregivers would come into the home to take care of his previous owner before she sadly passed away. We will recommend children over 8 due to his inexperience with small children. Jack is said to be not good with other animals. We haven't had an opportunity to test him and plan to look for a foster or adoptive home with no other pets and a fenced yard since this is what he is used to. 

Jack uses potty pads in the house and has not been going outside much due to the failing health of his owner. Jack recently spent time in a foster home and will need a securely fenced yard in his home. Jack was absolutely adored by his owner and we would love to find someone else for him to love him to pieces until the very end. He's a charming little guy with a lot of love to give. Jack is a quiet dog and doesn't bark much. 

Jack is neutered, up to date on vaccines, and heartworm negative.  His adoption fee is $100. If interested, please complete an application on our website at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting. One application works for all of our dogs. If interested in fostering, you provide the love and we provide any supplies you may need until we locate a forever home for Jack.

animal.description:
Clara is a quiet, cautious girl with a gentle soul that loves to snuggle.    It may take her a little while to completely snuggle in because she likes to take it slow.  She is a very sweet girl, and our foster mom thinks she’s very pretty too.


"C" Puppies bio: 

Hi everyone! 
We are the “C” puppies because all of our names begin with the letter “C”.  Our names are Carol, Clara, Charlie, Chester, and Champ.  We are about 12 to 14 weeks old.  Sorry, but we don’t remember exactly when we were born nor do we remember what breeds our mom and dad are.  Our foster mom says that we are beautiful puppies.  Is beautiful a breed?  We may look a lot alike, but our personalities are very different.  
Onto the boring stuff. We have all been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, and microchipped.  However, we will need another set of puppy vaccinations when we’re a tad bit older.  The vet said that we are ready to find our forever homes!  We all currently weigh between 13 and 16 pounds.
So, if you are looking for a friendly, sweet puppy and you think one of us would make a good addition to your family please let the people at Toledo’s Pet Bull Project know by going to www.toledospetbullproject.com and filling out an application.  There is no cost and no obligation to fill out an application.  However, there is a small adoption fee of $225 to help cover the cost of our vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter, etc.  There is also an additional $50 training fee that is refundable when you take us to a puppy training class.

We hope to meet you soon!

Please note donations using the SPONSOR ME tab will not go to Fluffy Dog Rescue.

To Locate Our Application go to http://rescue.fluffydog.net/how-to-adopt.html

Our listings are updated throughout the day. If there is an applicant, it will say PENDING ADOPTION next to the dog's name. If not, please submit an Application that can be found on our site, www.fluffydog.net. 

MY AGE: approx. 1 year  WEIGHT: approx. 50 lbs.  WHERE I AM FROM: AL (arrival 1/30) 

MY STORY: Jasper is the best boy. He did break his front foot at some time and also lost the outside toe and part of the foot. With that said, our vet said he is not in pain and is using it so does not need attention. There will not be wear that will cause sores, which is something we worry about in these instances. He does walk with a limp. The break may have been at the ankle, so from the ankle down is what he uses as a foot. He runs and plays and wonders why everyone is so concerned about his foot. Let's go!

Dogs are held for two weeks after arrival date. You are welcome to apply, but applications will be processed closer to the available date.

Dogs needing foster homes are available for adoption This dog does need a foster home. Have you ever considered fostering a dog?  For more information, see the Fluffy dog rescue home page. This dog does shed and is not hypoallergenic.

HOUSEBROKEN?   GOOD WITH DOGS?    GOOD WITH CATS?unknown

ADOPTION FEE: $450

To adopt the FIRST STEP is to complete an APPLICATION. The application can be found on our site www.fluffydog.net, or by clicking on the purple Fluffy Dog Rescue wording found in the left corner of this page under the dogs name.

Our dogs are located in foster homes throughout the state. We do not have a facility. Adopters must be 24 years old.We can not adopt to families with children under the age of six. We also adopt in WI, IL, and parts of MN. Most of our dogs are strays, so the breed is our best guess.
WI License #270548.
 
Check out Fluffy Dog Wellness on our Home Page. Great Solutions to Enhance Your Pet's Health. www.fluffydog.net

Twinkie is a cute male poodle mix about 3 years old and 11 pounds. He was found as a stray by a good citizen who asked us to take him into our program. 

IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG:
Please go to our Website: Poodlerescueofhouston.org and see the section: "Steps 2 Adoption". There will be a drop down menu where you must read and meet all of the prerequisites. Next, read the "Steps To Adoption", fill out the "Interest Form" and submit it online. THIS IS THE ONLY WAY TO APPLY. Unfortunately, we are unable to respond to inquires made in any other way.

Poodle Rescue will contact you if we feel this dog, or a similar dog in our program, matches the specifications on your Questionnaire/Interest Form. Please keep in mind Poodles and Poodle Mixes are in high demand therefore the demand for them far outweigh the supply. If you do not hear from us please re-submit your Interest form quarterly as they are not recurring. Unfortunately, we cannot answer email or telephone inquiries about our available dogs.  Please be sure you have a current phone number listed on the questionnaire/Interest Form and the best time we can reach you. Adoption Fees vary.

All dogs are spayed/neutered, current on shots, parasite / heart worm disease tested (and treated if positive).  All dogs are microchipped, groomed and use a dog door at our facility.

animal.description:
Poor Ford came to FOPAS so frightened that he would hardly come out of his kennel and walks were just scary.  After several weeks of a good place to live, care, and mostly lots of attention and LOVE, Ford has become a real dog who now comes bouncing out of his kennel and running up to everyone looking for the beloved treat.  But big trucks and school busses still scare him.   Ford is an Australian Shepherd mix with an estimated DOB of 9/2017.  Aussies are known to be anti-social with other dogs unless they are socialized young, and Ford was not, so he'll need to be an only dog.  And being a herding dog, he would probably do better in a home with no small children.  Anyone who first meets FORD may think that he, like many Aussies, is a little standoffish, but for us, having seen how far he has come so quickly,  and knowing how very very smart he is, we know that he isn't standoffish for long, he loves attention from people and he loves being part of human activities.  Ford keeps his kennel so clean that he is always the easiest to clean up after.  This is a dog that just needs a chance at a happy life. 

If you are interested in Ford, please fill out an application here:
https://www.parkvilleshelter.com/adoption-application

This sweet girl is Talia.  She is a super smart 4 month old heeler mix who weighs 21 lbs but will be about 42 lbs full grown.  Talia was rescued from a local shelter with demodex mange.  She has recovered and is furry, happy and healthy now.  

Talia is perfect according to her foster mom.  She is so smart!  She sits on command, knows stay, and has done excellent with her crate/house training.  Talia rides well in a car, loves to play, and loves to cuddle up with her people.  She also enjoys a super comfy bed to sleep in.  Talia is great with kids!

Talia would like a home where she has a fenced in yard and an active family.  She would make a great companion for a family with kids old enough to play with her, cuddle her, and give her lots of exercise.  

Talia is doing excellent with her potty training (she rings a bell now), kennel trained, and walks well on a leash. 

Talia is spayed, microchipped, and current on her vaccines.  Her adoption fee is $175.  

If you would like to adopt Talia and make her a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

animal.description:
PLEASE, PLEASE READ  carefully.  Most of your questions will be answered in this biography.

Sweet HOOK will be placed in his pre-approved adoptive home around the end of February after his neuter.  

HOOK was born to  Mom Sandy (see photo)  in the safety of a wonderful foster home.  We are so glad that he and his ten (yes, ten!) littermates made it to safety in time for the blessed event.  

HOOK  is a baby (born December 28, 2020)  and wants a home that understands the world of puppies. He will only be placed in a loving home that is dedicated to work on house training, leash manners, and will introduce him to a variety of safe activities and experiences so he can be comfortable in the world. 

While we never had the pleasure of meeting Baby Daddy, Mom, Sandy, is a gorgeous Retriever Mix that weighs about 40 lbs. However, HOOK may grow to be smaller, the same size, or larger, at adulthood and with a similar or different "look."

Puppies are immunized on a strict vet recommended schedule, and HOOK's forever family will be required, at their own expense, to complete the puppy immunization schedule, including rabies, if placed in your home prior to the schedule being completed.  Adopters are provided with current vetting records to provide to their personal vet, and we will confirm that you DO complete that vetting schedule in a timely manner, including the purchase of monthly preventatives (flea & heart worm).   HOOK will be neutered & microchipped  before being placed in his forever home.

For more information on our adoption process, please visit our website at www.youluckydogrescue.org and read our Adoption FAQ's and Before You Adopt documents. You can complete an online adoption application from our website. You can also email info@youluckydogrescue.org for additional details that are not included in this biography.

PRIVATE MEET & GREETS: Submitting an adoption application is required before a private meet & greet will be scheduled. We will complete a pre-screening first to make sure that the dog you are interested in is a good fit for you. That way, we don't unnecessarily waste your time or the foster's time. 

Our adoption fee is $300 and includes all age-appropriate vaccines, spay or neuter and microchipping. All of our rescue dogs are heart worm tested annually beginning at 9 months of age, and they are kept on monthly heart worm and flea preventatives.

The breed and age included in this listing is based upon the opinion of a vet that has examined the dog. We cannot confirm the age of the dog unless the dog was born in the care of the rescue. 

We are located in the metro Atlanta area. We currently do not allow out of state adoptions as a home check is required as part of the adoption process.

www.youluckydogrescue.org - Adoption Application can be found at this website.

animal.description:
****Please do not message the rescue asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO BEFORE EMAILING****

*Name: SIMBA
*Age: 1.5 years
*Current Weight: 90#
*Rescued from: Rural Texas, owner surrendered for "Too big & energetic" 
*Adoption fee: $375 
*Health: Up to date vaccinations, heartworm negative, neutered

Simba is a gorgeous, big, goofy & energetic Great Dane mixed with a Mastiff. Simba is a big boy & he will need a family who has experience with his breed. He loves to play & is dog friendly. He does need a playmate who understands his size & energy. Simba is smart & loves to please his person. He knows some basic commands, is crate trained & does great in the car. Simba has always lived in a home & was house trained. He is good with all people BUT he is big & has no clue of his size. Simba will need a home with older children only because he is big & bouncy. Simba loves to cuddle & hug, we are working with him on not hugging unless asked to. He is a staff favorite & loved by all who meet him. Simba needs a fenced yard & would love to have a playmate but that is not a requirement. 
 
Simba was rescued from an area where there is an abundance of homeless dogs, and not a lot of shelter space for them to go while they wait for their forever homes. He will be arriving at SNARR's Adoption Center in Brewster, NY on 1/23/2020 ready for adoption! To apply to adopt Simba, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**
 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING
-------------------------------------------------------
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Coolio is a 9-year-old, 64-pound charmer. He's in need of a new home after his owner passed away.

If you think fetch is fun, then Coolio might your guy. His other favorite hobby is hanging out with his family. This gentle giant was house trained in his previous home. He is also accustomed to using a crate. Coolio lived with an older family and has never met young kids.

Coolio has lived with multiple dogs in his previous home. He is picky about what dogs he likes, and would do best with a a polite dog who will not try to steal his beloved ball. He has never lived with cats.

Upon admission, the vets at Lollypop Farm identified masses on Coolio's body, some of which are not safe to surgically remove. After sending a sample for biopsy, they determined that they are mostly mast cell tumors. Mast cell tumors can metastasize to internal organs, so Coolio's new owner will work with their vet to keep a close eye on his condition and determine what treatment or interventions are needed. Chemotherapy or radiation may be options for Coolio, but are outside the scope of what we can provide at the shelter.

If Coolio sounds like the right dog for you, click the orange "Schedule An Appointment" box above to make an appointment to meet with an Adoption Counselor.

animal.description:
Beckham is ready to bend it with you!  This sporty spice girl is looking for someone to play with. She is very fit, agile, athletic and energetic, not to mention very smart. Highly trainable with enough food and toy drive to potentially make a great dog sport or performance partner.

She currently displays some unruly teen behavior, typical of a poorly socialized adolescent Malinois, and will need a human partner to help her mature into a proper lady. Our handling team has been working with her on some behavior management and certain canine citizenship skills and will expect any adopter to be willing to maintain and build on her progress so far. 

Beckham came to us from a shelter in Elk Grove, CA where she was picked up as a stray after a family saw her wandering and get hit by a car, when an officer arrived at the scene, Beckham was carrying on with her wander without a care, showing no signs of injury after all. 

She has all the qualities we look for in search dogs--love for toys, love for food, love for the hunt, love for action--but just not quite enough for her to be a working dog.

She will be most successful with those who have prior breed experience as Mals can be Mals. She can be reactive to other dogs while on leash, go over threshold quickly if stimulated, wants and needs to do things. No cats, please. No small children. A secure yard or living space, as she is an escape artist.

The AKC describes the Belgian Malinois like this: to deny a Mal activity and the pleasure of your company is to deprive them of their very reasons for being. Beckham would agree with this. Are you game enough to offer her the pleasure of your company?

Beckham is 10 months old and weighs 45 lbs. She is up to date on vaccinations and will be spayed before release.

animal.description:
**WE ARE CURRENTLY DOING ADOPTIONS BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. YOU MUST CALL TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING. PLEASE LEAVE US A VOICEMAIL IF YOU ARE UNABLE TO REACH US. THANK YOU FOR YOUR PATIENCE AND UNDERSTANDING.- CCDP STAFF**

Hi there. My name is Jance. I'm about 5 years old and I weigh about 57 lbs. 
I was picked up by the pound after being chained to a telephone pole on a backroad one night. 
I was very afraid at first and I didn't really want to let people get too close to me, but after being here at the pound for a while, I have learned that it is okay to trust people and I've been doing great. 
I LOVE LOVE LOVE playing fetch. I'm pretty smart and pick up on things pretty quickly. 
I am very clean in my kennel at night and I appear to be housebroken. 
If you're looking for a sweet dog to add to your family, please consider adopting me.

Our adoption fee is $150.00. The pound DOES NOT accept checks for adoption fees. We're able to accept cash for adoption OR Visa/ Mastercard/ Discover Card. A convenience fee of 2.39% will be applied to all credit/ debit card adoptions. If you intend to do a foster-to-adopt, the fee must be cash. ALL dogs/puppies adopted from our shelter will receive their parvo distemper vaccine, bordetella vaccine, rabies vaccine (if aged at 12 weeks or older), be dewormed with a 3 day course of panacur dewormer, be microchipped, receive their current Ohio dog license and will be spayed or neutered. ALL DOGS/PUPPIES WILL BE SPAYED OR NEUTERED unless a health issue prohibits the surgery from being performed. Not all dogs posted for adoption are spayed/ neutered yet. If you're driving a long distance to adopt, please verify that the vetting process has been completed and dog you're interested in adopting is still available for adoption. The above mentioned vetting is all included in your adoption fee. The adoption fee and what is included in the adoption fee is NON-NEGOTIABLE.

Adoptions MUST be done at the pound and in person as there is paperwork to fill out and an adoption contract that must be signed by the adopter. This means you must be willing to travel to our shelter to adopt.

IF the dog you're interested in adopting has medical conditions or injuries which require medical treatment, we ask that you help with the medical bills so we can continue to help the dogs coming in who need additional vet care.
We are a county run shelter, therefore we cannot control our intake or the health or behavior of the dogs that come in to our shelter.

Although we try our hardest to place all of our adoptable dogs, there are certain circumstances in which any dog in our care could be euthanized at any time and without further notice (IE: sudden untreatable medical condition or injury, temperament or behavioral problems which may not be apparent when the dog first arrives, lack or space, etc.), therefore all dogs at our shelter should be considered urgent. The adoption of a more highly adoptable dog will mean more time for the less adoptable dog in the kennel next to him!

Shelter hours are: Monday-Friday: 8 am- 4 pm
Saturday: 8 am - 11 am.
Sunday: 8 am - 11 am.
Adoptions are always welcome during hours of operation. We will make special arrangements for adoptions in advance.
There is nobody in the office on Saturday and Sunday, so therefore we are unable to answer or return phone calls over the weekend.

Can't adopt a dog? We would love to have more volunteers who are able to spend time with our dogs! The dogs LOVE going for walks and the socialization and exercise helps make the dogs more adoptable.

Contact information:
8455 County Home Road
Lisbon, OH 44432
(330)424-6663
Email: hpecorelli@ccclerk.org

Bruce is a 4 to 5 year old healthy, happy and well- rounded petite (45 pounds) black lab mix. Hes housebroken, super affectionate, loves kids, people, dogs, likes walks and walks great on a leash. He is a laid back, low maintenance dog. He knows sit, down, roll over, and mastering stay. Bruce will be happiest in a home with a fenced yard and someone home more than not that is willing to make him part of the family pack and take him on adventures!

 

To meet Bruce, visit us at www.dsda.org/adopt for additional information regarding our adoption criteria and submit our online adoption application.

 Adoption Fees:

Puppies (under 12 months) - $300+tax
Dogs (12 months and over) - $250+tax

Qualifications for Adoption: No dog is alike and each dog has different requirements based on breed, age, energy level and life experiences. DSDA is very careful to place our dogs in homes that we believe are the best fit for the dog based on our experience with each dog. All of our dogs live in foster homes which allows us the opportunity to learn about their individual needs. 


	Must be 21 years or older with identification showing present address.
	Must have the knowledge and consent of all adults living in the household.
	Vet checks are required. All resident animals must be spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations and on monthly heartworm and flea/tick preventative (if applicable).
	Must receive proof of pet deposit and lease allowing pets if renting.
	Willingness and capacity to spend the time and money necessary to provide training, medical treatment and responsible care for a pet.
	Applicant is home more than not.
	Any poisonous plants must be removed from the yard before the home visit.
	Home visit is required. For this reason, we adopt locally in the Dallas area.

Alfie was surrendered to a rural shelter with his sister, Tessa. The owner was moving & could no longer keep the siblings. Alfie is very friendly, loves to play & is happy go-lucky. He is smart & enjoy learning new things. Alfie is working on his house training skills and has little accidents, he is crate trained, does well on a leash but working on getting better & does well in a car.  He would do best in a home with older children (over the age of 7-8) because he can play and get a little rowdy.   He is used to living in a home & loves to curl up on the couch & cuddle with his human. 


*Adoption fee: $495 

*Health: Up to date vaccinations, heartworm negative, neutered

To apply to adopt this puppy, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 

**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING
-------------------------------------------------------
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records. Remember, most of the time rescues are all just taking our best guess with breeds!

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Nova Lee is a very lively and energetic Boxer Terrier, born April, 2016. She would love to go to an active home with lots of affection. She is friendly with all people - even strangers - but does not enjoy the company of other dogs. She will tolerate cats if properly introduced. Nova Lee loves toys but will need some training as she does resource guard her toys as well as bolt out the door. This sweet girl is move-in ready; she is kennel trained, house trained, and knows some commands. She needs to be crated when home alone as she can become destructive when bored. Nova Lees perfect home would be an active one with people who love to give and receive plenty of loveoh, and lots and lots of toys! She needs a fenced in yard - preferably a tall fence. No kids under 12 years old due to resource guarding.

The suggested adoption donation for Nova Lee is $350. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.
