animal.description:
Buddy was picked up as a stray and brought to a shelter in Baton Rouge, LA in March, during the height of COVID-19 when the shelter was short-staffed.   It saddens us to think that this sweet boy had spent so many months of his life in a shelter, but all of that is in his past! 

Buddy, came north in mid-September and was placed in what we hoped would be his forever home in NJ.  However, the environment of a townhouse community where they live had too much activity, and Buddy got too excited with so many dogs around.  He would be best suited in a quieter area in a home with a solidly fenced-in yard. 

Buddy is great with other dogs when he meets and plays with them, but he would do best as an only pet in the home.  When on leash, he gets excited when he sees another dog from a distance and will jump and bark, so he is currently working on his leash reactivity with a trainer.  Buddy is making great progress and looks forward to meeting his forever family. Buddy’s adopter will need to understand that the behavior is a work in progress and continue his training with a professional trainer.  His adopter will need to be fully committed to bringing Buddy along to be a happy and balanced dog.  If his adopter is in Norwalk, CT area, the adopter will have a chance to work with Buddy’s trainer.

Buddy learns commands and tricks quickly, has great manners around the house, and would learn your routine quickly. He sits as soon as he sees someone coming with a treat and takes it gently from their hand.  Buddy adores people, young and old, and at the sight of a person, Buddy wiggles so hard he can barely walk!  He loves lots of attention and likes to be right next to you or even in your lap.  He falls right to sleep at night or when you leave the house.  Buddy is housebroken and you’ll know when he needs to go out for a potty break because he’ll walk up to you, sit at your feet, and stretch his paw out!  He loves playing fetch and is a very energetic boy.  Like all young dogs, he will need an active adopter to give him the exercise he needs.  Buddy is a wonderful companion on a long hike.  However, he is just as happy cuddling up with you on the couch for hours - he’ll do anything for a good ear rub!  He is very expressive with his personality.

Buddy is believed to be a Nova Scotia Duck Tolling Retriever mix.  This little fellow is as cute as can be and is estimated to be about 1.5 years old.  He weighs only 32 lbs and is completely full-grown. Buddy’s size is perfect for just about anyone, especially those of us who are finding they want a smaller dog as we get older and cannot pick up a 90 lb dog.  He is a furry little bundle of total joy!

Buddy has been brought up-to-date on vaccinations, is neutered, micro-chipped, and he is heartworm negative. For the first year of adoption, he must be given the brand name Heartguard for his heartworm preventative. After that, a generic may be considered.  Like many dogs, Buddy has some seasonal allergies that gave him an itchy paw in the Fall.  His food allergies are controlled with his diet.

Rescued dogs come with a range of needs - from behavioral to emotional to medical.  When approved applicants adopt such dogs, they agree to continue the rehabilitation we have begun.  

If you would like to be part of Buddy's rescue story, and you have already been approved for adoption through SGRR, please contact Michelle Hamed at: SunshineMichelleH@gmail.com     to be considered to adopt Buddy.           

If not yet approved for adoption, please visit our website to learn more and to submit an online application:     http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com/adoption-info1.html  

Please DO NOT use the ASK ABOUT button to contact us, about this dog, as that will delay our ability to respond to your inquiry.  Please direct any questions regarding your application status to:  ajpillinger@gmail.com   

Thank you!
 
ABOUT OUR RESCUE
Before being approved to adopt, all potential adopters will be required to complete our online application and participate in our pre-adoption review process. The process includes the completion of an online application, a reference from the applicants' vet, a phone interview, and a visit to the applicants' home.  The application process helps us determine what type of Golden would be best suited for the applicants' life style.  In some cases, the specific dog you are interested in may have found a home before this process is complete or further assessment may indicate that this dog is not the right match for your family.  We are frequently getting new Goldens in need of a home, so we encourage you to apply and complete the application process so that when the right dog comes along you will be ready. 

The information provided on each dog is based on the observations of our vets, volunteers, fosters, and when available, trainers. While we do our best to report any and all issues, SGRR does not make any guarantees as to the health or temperament of any dog. Dogs evolve differently in different environments and we cannot predict with any certainty how the dog you adopt will behave and adapt in your home.

SGRR ADOPTION FEES - Effective May 1, 2020  (subject to change)
  
  $750    Puppy - up to 6 months              
  $650    Young 6 months - 6 years            
  $550    Senior 7 - 9  years                       
  $450    Senior 10 years and older          
 
  $550    Young Special Needs                
  $400    Senior 7+ Special Needs                

$1000    Young Bonded Pair                   
  $900    Senior 7+ Bonded Pair         

A contract is signed on the day of adoption.  Under the terms of the contract, all adopters are required to bring their SGRR dog to a vet within 7 business days.  All dogs receive basic veterinary care prior to adoption.  However, if an adopter's vet identifies an illness that an adopter is not willing to treat, then the dog may be returned and a full refund would be provided. 

Most of our dogs are fostered in private homes.  We do not have a facility to visit.  We are committed to our dogs before, during, and after adoption! To this end, the rescue retains an interest in each dog and our dogs can never be surrendered, re-homed, or sold. Should an adopter no longer be able to keep their SGRR dog, SGRR must be notified so that we can take the dog back into rescue and place it into another home. We reserve the right to remove a dog at any time should we find the adopter is no longer providing proper care.  Adopters agree to follow up visits as needed.  

Please be a ray of light for this Sunshine dog and make a tax deductible donation toward medical care and other expenses.   Every cent of your generosity goes directly toward the care of a Sunshine dog.

Please visit our website at: http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com  to learn more about our rescue and to make a Donation to support Sunshine Golden Retriever Rescue.  

THANK YOU!

My name is Grover! I've heard some people say that I have a funny shaped head, but everyone here loves me and tells me how adorable I am.

I am being tested for Masticatory muscle myositis (MMM) which is an immune system disorder in which the dog's immune system identifies the dog's own muscle tissue as foreign and attacks it. Sounds complicated right? I am being told this can cause issues or just be cosmetic. In my case it seems to be cosmetic.

I am looking for someone to love me for who I am. I promise my heart is even bigger than my ears and I will always be your best buddy!

**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING
-------------------------------------------------------
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
*Update* Maddie is still looking for a forever foster.  Please keep sharing!  
?Meet our sweet and lovable Maddie! She is an eight-year-old, Siberian Husky mix, looking for a forever foster home.
Maddie was rescued by our Humane Officer, after spending her entire life outside on a chain. Our Humane Officer discovered she was lethargic, underweight, and had a severe mammary tumor on her underside.  She knew she had to get her medical help right away. She was brought to the WAHS where our medical team jumped into action to do all they could for Maddie. She was treated for an infection and once her blood levels were stabilized, she received surgery to remove the mass. The surgery was successful, and Maddie is bouncing back! Unfortunately, after a biopsy, it was determined that her cancer will continue to spread. 
We are looking for a hospice foster, where she can spend the rest of her days in the comfort of a home. Her medical care and any other necessities will be supplied by the WAHS. All we want is for this sweet girl to receive the love and comfort she truly deserves while she still can. She is a staff favorite and frequently spends time visiting different offices and taking naps.  She is a curious girl who loves to be by your side, and still enjoys a short, daily walk.  
? Maddie’s preferred foster home would be a quiet one. After a careful assessment by our trainer, it was determined she cannot be in a home with any other pets. Due to her medical condition and the current healing process, she requires a foster home with older/adult children. If you are interested in opening your home to Maddie’s big heart and beautiful blue and brown eyes, please contact our Foster Coordinator at 724-470-9708 or Foster@washingtonpashelter.org.

Missy is a 5-year-old female Beagle mix. She is calm, sweet, housebroken and well mannered inside the house. She has gotten a little "growly" with younger kids in the past, so if there are any kids in the home, we are requiring them to be older than 10 and respectful. Missy is currently 45 lbs and on a weight loss plan. Her ideal adopter would be committed to helping her get to her ideal weight. We are requiring a secure fenced-in yard for Missy.

If you live in the central Florida (Orlando) area and think you have the perfect forever home for Missy, we'd love to find out more about you. Please fill in our adoption application and we'll see if you're Missy's perfect match.

animal.description:
HSMC Adoption applications must be done at www.hsmcohio.org Please do NOT click on the "Adopt Me" button on this bio. It is only a pet inquiry. If you have additional questions about this dog, please call the shelter at 614-879-8368 or contact us through our website!

Hi! My name is Spot and I'm in search for my forever home! 
I'm a terrier mix, around 2 years old, weighing about 50 pounds! My people tell me I'm an amazing boy and I think so too. I'm looking for a new home because my first owner passed away from a heart attack, although my story is a sad one, I'm ready for my happy ending. I did test positive for heartworms, but don't let that stop you from meeting me because the people of HSMC are getting me all fixed up and ready to find a home to call mine. While I go through all my treatments and medications, I REALLY want to go to a foster home, that will hopefully be my forever home when I'm done with my treatments! I'm as sweet as they come, and always ready to be out and about on a short walk, or just hanging out inside with my people, chewing on a toy or soaking up as much love as I can get. I like other dogs, but I can't play with them just yet, because it's important that I have to stay calm. In my old home, I didn't like the kitty, I thought it was just something I had to chase, so I need to go to a home without. As far as young kids, they make me a little nervous, but I like older kids that can play with me! I'm a very clean boy, I don't like to make messes in my kennel, I will always hold it until I can go outside. I'm such a good boy, always wanting to please and spread all my love to everyone! I'm constantly seeking for affection, as getting love is my favorite thing ever, and I like to return the love by giving cuddles and kisses! I'm a pretty smart boy too! I know how to sit, laydown and stay (treats are always a bonus)! I cannot wait to meet my forever family and share my endless amounts of love!

Our adoption fees vary, Shelter Dogs are $150, Prison Dogs are $200, Puppies are $250, and Popular Pure-Breeds are $400. Hey everyone! We are Saint and Felix! We were thrown from a car in South Carolina and a wonderful family saw it and brought us home. We don't know why someone would want to dump us on the streets, but we know we will hit the jackpot soon with a family that will love us forever! We are very happy boys and love everyone we meet! We are dog friendly but prefer not to live with cats. We love to play outside and cuddle. We are low to medium energy. We can be playful when you want, but also cuddly when you want. We enjoy walks and riding in the car. We are super sweet and will love anyone immediately. We have been through a lot and we are just hoping to find someone that can be there for us forever! 

Saint is the all brown one and he is around 2 years old. Felix is the brindle one and he is around 1 year old. Their adoption fee is $750 for the pair.

animal.description:
Puck is a 2-year-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, 4dx/heartworm tested, and spayed/neutered. This dog is also tested with other dogs, kennel-trained, and housebroken. Puck is cat-friendly and is playful with cats. We would love for you to meet this dog and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
Jack is an 11yo lab mix who is blind and mostly deaf. He has quite the story, read about it below! 

"Jack is a complete sweetheart who has been on a JOURNEY lately, literally and figuratively. Last year he was living with the family he’d been with his whole life in a small town in Tennessee when he suddenly went blind. For some reason, his people surrendered him to a vet’s office, where he lived in a kennel in a back building for several months. Thanks to a Facebook post, he was brought to Portland by a series of amazing volunteers driving (and even flying) him over 2000 miles across the country in hopes of finding a new home. Now that he’s been here a couple months, lost some weight, and recovered from a bout of pneumonia he’s ready to find his people! Jack is completely blind and also doesn’t hear very well at all. He’s been working on how to communicate with his foster dad, and a free session with an experienced special needs trainer is included with his adoption so he can keep progressing. Jack would enjoy a mellow home with some very patient adults who can continue working with him to further improve his confidence, physical strength, and navigation skills. He’s good in a crate and great in the car and is VERY food motivated and responds well to positive training. Jack doesn’t need a lot of exercise and likes to just relax in his bed somewhere near his person, and is fully housetrained and can go for quite some time between potty breaks. He hasn’t done particularly well with small children in the past but he would probably be fine with well-mannered and supervised kids. He is good with other dogs -- he currently has four foster siblings -- but prefers them on the calmer side, and cats are an unknown (but he doesn’t move very fast). Jack's new home should have minimal steps since they're a challenge for him to navigate, and ideally a fenced yard for him to freely explore. "

If you are interested in Jack please fill out the application at the link below

http://www.deafdogsoforegon.org/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
Sabrina is a happy go lucky spirited girl. She loves attention from anyone and everyone and is not shy at all! Sabrina has a lot of energy that she loves to get out on walks, playing tug, and rough housing. She doesn’t have a prey drive towards cats, but she will chase them in a playful way (and doesn’t take no for an answer!), so dog savvy cats would be best. She is cool with other dogs. Ideally, if Sabrina has a canine sibling, they would be a larger dog. Sabrina is so happy all around, but sometimes her happiness and energy come off as a lack of manners and boundaries. She is very smart, though, and her foster mom has been working on leash manners and food time manners to start. So far Sabrina has gone from refusing to go in her crate to going in on command, jumping and lunging for her food to sitting and waiting for permission to eat. While her manners still have a long way to go, her potential and desire to please her humans will make that very easy to address. Due to her size and energy, Sabrina is looking for a home with no human kiddos under the age of 12 years

To meet Sabrina, please visit our website, www.pittieslovepeace.com, to submit an adoption application. Sabrina is spayed, microchipped and vaccinated. 

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing a predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Hi there! I'm Exegol. I love having a job to do. I'm doing well on my crate training here at the shelter and in my foster home. I still have more to learn when I find a new home, so I'd do best with dog savvy older kids in the home. Come meet me at the Allen County SPCA today!

Weight: 66.40

Adoption Price: $100

WANT TO TAKE ME HOME TODAY? SCHEDULE AND ADOPTION APPOINTMENT.
To Schedule An Adoption Appointment:
1. Fill out and submit our online Adoption Application.
2. Please only submit ONE Adoption Application. (Our Application is for general pre-approval, not for a specific adoptable animal).
3. Once received, the Allen County SPCA will review your application. Applications are reviewed in the order they are received.
4. We will contact you to let you know your Adoption Status and schedule an Adoption Appointment. Applications may take up to 1-2 days to process. Please give us a call at the shelter at 260-744-0454 if you have not heard back from us within 48 hours.
5. If you haven't found your perfect match at the shelter, that's okay too - pre-approved applications are valid for 6 months!

Come prepared! Please bring proof of a current rabies vaccine for all pets living in the home. If you have another dog, you are welcome to bring him or her with you so that we can safely perform a dog interaction.

Unfortunately, animals cannot be held for you.

A Special Note from the Allen County SPCA:
Remember, pets are a lifelong commitment. We at the Allen County SPCA ask that you take adding a furry family member to your home seriously, and do your research on the different breeds before adopting. We also ask that you are able to keep up on yearly vaccinations, monthly preventatives, a good diet, daily exercise, training, and most of all, LOVE. If you ever have an issue with a pet that you adopted, please contact us right away; we may be able to help, or we can put you in touch with someone who can. All set? Come in and adopt today!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Sadie & I'm a 10 year old female beagle. I need a home because my person passed away. I've lived all my life with 2 other female beagles outside as a hunting dog. I'm the mother of the other beagles on the Nittany Beagle Rescue website who lived outside as hunting dogs. I'm in a foster home now & I'm LOVING it! I loved the bath my foster mom gave me, & I adore having my head & back rubbed! I like to stick right by my foster family.    I'm making great progress on housetraining & house manners. I'm very smart! I'm learning fast about living in a home.  I'm still a little jumpy, & I might be that way for awhile. This is all really, really different for me. Because I haven't been around young children, I will be placed in a home with older children (8-12 years) or no children. I need a home where I will have a securely fenced yard. I have been known to dig under a fence, so it needs to be secure. I will run off looking for bunnies to chase if I get loose. I don't know how to walk on a leash, & so that is something I need to learn. Because I never went anywhere, I'm pretty timid in new situations. I'm a big girl - about 40 lbs.  I will be spayed before I'm adopted. I also have a mammary tumor that will be removed when I'm spayed. I'm anxious to become part of a family as a member of the household, enjoying life on the couch! Please think about making me part of your family!

animal.description:
Vinny was rescued from a shelter. He was neglected and emaciated. The shelter fed him extra food to help him gain some weight in the past 2 weeks. Vinny is a sweetie and charming to all people and dogs. With an over-excited large dog he just backed away. He is cooperative loves treats and is ready to learn. Vinny is a sweetie and is now relaxing at his hero foster home with 2 other dogs. More info. to come as he learns relaxes gets healthier and heals from his neuter surgery and shows more of his personality. Needs a home with an attached yard.
Update from Foster Home 1/30/21: Vinny was a stray picked up in poor condition extremely underweight. The shelter and foster parents have helped him put on weight by feeding him lots of healthy and nutritious food. He now looks fantastic with a beautiful shiny coat.
He is a very sweet dog would like to be a lapdog and quite submissive he lives with a much smaller dog (who is a boss) and a cat he gets on really well with both of them. He is quite rambunctious at times so children need to be 12+ he is only young so has lots of energy. He will require walking twice a day for a couple of miles each time and also loves long hikes (although nervous of people he's getting better). He's great on the leash and walks really well without the need for correction and is not leash aggressive.
Vinny loves to be with you in the day and would suit a house with at least somebody around most of the day and a backyard to play in. He curls up in the day after his walk and snoozes and settles well at night. He is mostly house trained (requires going out every two hours in the day) with the occasional accident if he gets stressed or over-excited but he will overcome this. He is crate trained and happy to go in it in the day if necessary and sleeps well at night. He requires lots of attention guidance and kisses and will be your shadow where I go he goes he's super sweet and will be a fabulous companion.
He currently walks 40 mins twice a day and up to 8-mile hikes at the weekend. He has energy and needs a very active guardian with experience. Need a home with an attached back yard. Kids 12 yrs+.

animal.description:
Baxter and Jackson prove the concept that opposites definitely attract. These two fellows are bonded to each other and are absolute BFFs. Baxter is a gorgeous blond caramel color, while Jackson has shiny onyx black fur. Both are very sweet and beautiful boys that can’t wait to meet their forever family.

Baxter is one years old and weighs about 60 pounds. He is excellent with all dogs and likes to play with his foster brothers — especially his bestie Jackson. Baxter is medium energy. He also likes to play with toys. While Baxter is submissive and slower to warm up to people, he comes around once he knows you. In fact, Baxter’s foster mom writes that she loves how “Baxter is so loyal and once you gain his trust he is always by your side.” He pulls a little on his leash but loves to be outside in the fresh air. He also is a great car passenger. Baxter is good in his crate and must be crated if unsupervised. He needs a refresher on most commands but as his confidence and trust grows, he’ll be a wonderful student.

Jackson is 4 years old and weighs about 54 pounds. A medium energy pup, Jackson is the life of the party and is super friendly. No dog or person is a stranger to this outgoing pup. He plays well with all his doggo friends. He loves toys—especially kongs. He self crates and stays there when his people aren’t home. He is very smart and already knows sit, down and stay. He is eager to please and will be an avid student to learn how to keep all four on the floor, as well being less vocal. He is good with children and even sleeps in bed with his FM’s daughter. He is a good on the leash and is also an excellent passenger for car rides. His FM says that this dream dog is one of the easiest fosters she’s ever had.

Jackson is the ying to Baxter’s yang, and they bring out the best in each other. Both pups are super sweet, and adore each other. They have not been observed around cats so can’t go to a cat home, but they are approved for Guinea pigs! This beautiful pair would be a perfect twosome for a fun loving forever family.

Disclaimer: Please know this is a recently rescued dog that is still transitioning into a new home environment. Training, and even personality and energy levels are constantly evolving as the dog starts to feel better emotionally and physically. Your new dog will take days or even weeks to fully settle into his or her true self. What you read in this bio is a snapshot of this dog’s evolving personality. animal.description:
Meet JJ! This unique boy with the big brown eyes, radar ears and bushy tail was rescued from a hoarding situation, living in a dilapidated, trash-filled outdoor pen. Worthy Dog has rescued three other dogs from the property who needed medical care and rehabilitation. JJ was heartworm positive on intake, under-socialized and underweight, and going without consistent food, water, or any exposure to the outside world. He was initially very skittish and needed time to decompress, but his local foster parents have done a great job working with him and exposing him to new things, and helping him learn to trust. He's now been treated for heartworm and is ready to start his new life.

JJ is living in the Park View area of DC with two other dogs in his foster home. He connects very quickly to the other dogs and finds comfort in pup companionship. We feel another dog in the home is a requirement for JJ to be at his best. He would also do better in a quieter area. He's still fearful of many sights and sounds in the city.

His foster mom, Cynthia, checked in with these updates:

Energy Level: JJ is a moderate energy dog. He is calm inside the home and content to snuggle with you on the couch, but does need and enjoy his daily walks and exercise. He gets excited when we get his leash for walks, and will now allow us to put his harness on without scampering away.

Leash Walking Skills: JJ gets excited for his walks, although he's still nervous around busy intersections. He's happiest when there aren't many vehicles on the road. He ignores other dogs on his walks and is not reactive, but still needs some practice on his leash skills.

Personality: He's such a sweetheart and loves attention! He's not overly needy, but will definitely paw at your hand when he feels he deserves some affection. JJ is a great companion and allows us to pick him up and cuddle him when his humans need attention too! He's the type of pup that will seek you out when need be, but also likes to be with his canine buddies.

House Manners (crate/potty training): He's crate trained, although he's still working on getting in willingly. Potty training has vastly improved--he gets the concept of going outside, but you have to remain consistent as he may have accidents if he's not on a strict schedule. He's great with our other dogs and loves to cuddle with them!

JJ is a very loving, affectionate pup who LOVES other dogs. He was a little timid with his foster parents at first, but once he's warms up, he's very connected to his people. He needs a patient owner to settle him in and will do best in a calm home environment. We really feel he needs another dog in the home to help him better acclimate. Coming from a hoarding situation, his entire community was other dogs, and he finds comfort in them. JJ is still spooked by traffic/noises, so he's not the best city/condo dog.

FOSTER UPDATE - 1/23/21 - "It took a few weeks but JJ has really settled in. He plays now, and has a really cute personality. He's not as jumpy or skittish to sudden noises. He still follows our pups around and is very connected to other dogs. He would love a playmate in his new home. He's a great dog and it's going to be hard to see him go."

Requirements:

Quiet suburban setting

Needs another social, calm dog in the home

BREED ESTIMATE: Rat Terrier/Basenji mix
GENDER: Male
APPROXIMATE WEIGHT: 21 - 22 lbs
APPROXIMATE AGE: ~ 3 to 4 years
COAT TYPE: Medium
ADOPTION FEE: $400
OTHER INFO: utd on shots/neutered/microchipped/treated for heartworm
LOCATION: Washington, DC

FOR MORE INFO OR TO ADOPT: Please go to https://adopt.worthydog.org and complete the application.

You can also help save dogs like this one by becoming a foster, providing a rescue dog with a temporary home and giving them the love and care they need until they are permanently adopted. Every person who fosters is directly responsible for saving the life of a dog, because we can only save as many dogs as we have foster families available to welcome them into their homes. If you think you might be interested in becoming a foster and want to learn more, please go to https://foster.worthydog.org and fill out an application.

Worthy Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue that primarily adopts to families in the DC Metro area.

animal.description:
Buddy is a 5-year-old Shepherd and Rottweiler mix. He's a little unsure of new people and needs a little time to warm up. His ideal adopter would be someone who is experienced and can show him the ropes.
Sadly, Buddy has tested positive for heart-worms, due to this he will need an owner who can provide him with a calm environment while he goes through treatment and celebrates with him as he recovers! I weigh about 50 lbs and am medium sized.

I would love to come home with you for the holidays!

animal.description:
Storm - in Maine - updated January 2021

Storm is your typical victim of the Christmas puppy – the family wanted a new dog, the dad decided they could only have one so they turned her into a southern shelter right before Christmas. She is about 65 pounds of sweetness and energy. Her breed was listed as lab/great dane mix but since she is already two years old she won’t be growing into great dane size ; 0 )

She walks nicely on a leash if there are no distractions but can be a puller, especially if other dogs or people are around. We are going to get some training support for Storm so she can easily be handled on leash for her new family.  She sits on command and is learning “down”.

An active family is a must for Storm and we think she would bowl over young children. The shelter thought a dog of similar size and energy would be the best type of match but we are finding that she may want to be an only dog in her new home. Storm rides well in the car in a crate and is a happy sweet girl! Her vet checked her out thoroughly because her original paperwork indicated she had surgery last year to put a pin in her femur. We don’t know what type of trouble she got herself into but she is healthy and not slowed down at all now!

If you have interest in meeting Storm or any of our cuties, please fill out the adoption application here: http://www.luckypuprescue.org/adoption-application.

Please note: we do not have a physical facility where our dogs are housed; they are cared for in our wonderful foster network throughout New England. It is our expectation that, once approved, a potential family will meet the dog(s) in the foster setting where they are feeling safe and loved.

Thank you for considering rescue!

animal.description:
A FUN FRIEND FOR YOU:  1 year old / 46 lbs. 

Hi there!  My name is Maxx!  I came to Mostly Mutts from animal control and am so happy to be part of the Mostly Mutts family as I look for my furever home!  

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  I haven’t officially met other dogs at Mostly Mutts yet, but I will be dog tested soon.  I seemed interested in them from afar while on my walks, so if you have a nice doggie at home already, let’s meet with my trainer and see if we can be friends / I was quite agitated when I spotted a kitty through the window while in my short break foster home, so I should probably not live with cats / I am possessive of my toys and can be a bit dominant, so best there not be children in my new home.

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I am playful.  In fact, my foster described me as a ‘play all day’ kind of guy.  I am an athletic fellow who needs regular exercise, or I get bored and can get into mischief.  I can sometimes be head strong and want things my way, so I am looking for a dog savvy leader that will help me become a good follower.  I am affectionate, but when I’m tired, it seems that I want that on my terms. I have snapped a couple of times but did not bite down – once over unwanted affection and a couple of times over resource guarding my toys / My energy level is 6-8 so let’s be active together!

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I am now a student in the Mostly Mutts University training program, where I am learning lots of great doggie commands with my trainer, including working on my resource guarding behaviors.  I know the ‘sit’ and ‘down’ commands, and take my training treats nicely.  Check back soon to see my progress / I wasn’t crated in my short break foster home, as I resisted going in it.  My crate manners at Mostly Mutts have been good / I had a couple of accidents on the first days in my short break foster home, but I have done well on a good schedule.

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I like toys, though I tend to destroy soft ones, so be sure they are sturdy for strong chewers.  I love to play with Kongs or anything else I can fetch.  When not playing, I enjoy receiving affection on my terms / I don’t like to share my stuff, and I will be working on this with my training, so I can be a great companion to my people.

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and neutered.

I am looking for a great family dedicated to my training and to giving me the loving home all dogs deserve!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

animal.description:
Courtesy Post (Washington, DC) Meet adorable Duncan!
If you are looking for a handsome, smart, loving, active family pup, Duncan is the boy for you!

Duncan

AKA Dunk
is a loving 45-pound ball of energy, with the brains to keep up! He's a 1.5-year-old pit bull terrier mix and lives in a small apartment in the city, but at his age, he's too active for city life and is looking for a new home in the quieter suburbs where he can do some of his favorite things, which include running, tugging on his tough toys, and learning new things.

Duncan

loves
the great outdoors and would thrive in a home with an active family where he will get 3+ walks a day or would be able to go on daily hikes unless it's raining, in which case, he prefers quick potty breaks then back into the dry house. Due to his high energy, a fenced yard and neighborhood walks, or hikes would be ideal so can run around and get his zoomies out. Dog parks are not a good fit for him.

Duncan is house-broken and has learned basic commands of sit, down, stand, and wait and has started on settle training with a mat too!

He has his basic manner-commands down and is very treat motivated and willing to learn which makes him an excellent candidate for some basic training.

He loves ALL food and is willing to bend over backwards (or at least roll-over) to earn a treat. After a long hard day on the couch,
Duncan
enjoys play time and long walks around the neighborhood. By the end of the evening, all he wants is to curl up on your lap or snuggle by your side. He will make his way into your heart very quickly.

Duncan

would LOVE to be in a home with someone interested in working on basic reactivity training as he can get overly excited by his surroundings. He is a smart pup and learns quickly. He will be excited to learn new tricks or work for food puzzles. Being a young pup, h
e

can
get over-excited
so he needs a family who will be patient with him and will help work on relaxation and work to get his energy out. He does well in his crate, and he retreats to it as his safe, relaxing space when he needs some quiet time.

Duncan's energy level and tendency towards rough play make him the ideal candidate for a house or townhouse with a yard, without cats or young kids (kids ages 10+) and he should

likely be the only pet in the home.

He has gotten along with calmer dogs after a slow introduction.

He would do great
in

animal.description:
Bailey - in Maine - updated January 2021

Bailey just had a birthday! She is a 1 yr. old 50 lb boxer mix who needs a savvy individual or family to help her through the next phase of learning. She is a lovable and snuggly girl when she is tired out but she is a busy one! Bailey has not had a lot of limits put on her in her past so she has learned to push them. She is very responsive to training and has been working with our friends at Kompletely K9 Dog Training and Rehabilitation to help her become the awesome girl she can be! She responds to clear expectations.

Bailey is not a crate lover but needs it to keep her safe from chewing, counter-surfing and general mischief. She uses an indestructible crate right now which will be an investment for a new family. Bailey is learning “place” and is learning she doesn’t need to guard resources, especially not the humans in her life. She seems to like most dogs but she wants to be the boss of them if she doesn’t have limits set for her.

Bailey likes young people but with her tendency to boss around and guard, we think that older kids would be the best for her so that she doesn’t treat little ones as packmates.

A new owner will need to be experienced with dog ownership and be willing to follow up with training for Bailey.

If you have interest in meeting Bailey or any of our cuties, please fill out the adoption application here: http://www.luckypuprescue.org/adoption-application.

Please note: we do not have a physical facility where our dogs are housed; they are cared for in our wonderful foster network throughout New England. It is our expectation that, once approved, a potential family will meet the dog(s) in the foster setting where they are feeling safe and loved.

Thank you for considering rescue!

Grace arrived at the shelter on 1-10-21 and is now available for adoption. Grace is a Border Collie mix who is around 5-6 years old. Her first day was tail tucked and head down and she just didn't know what was happening to her. With a lot of love and reassures from the staff Grace has came out of her shell. This girl is so low key and the sweetest thing you will meet. She loves her treats and lots of love. She is greet in her kennel and she likes to go outside and patrol the yard to make sure we are safe. Grace will be spayed and given a rabies vaccination before going to her new home.  

Approved adoption applications will be contacted for an appointment.

If you are interested in putting in an application on this animal, please copy and paste the link below to fill out our application for adoption. https://siloamsprings.seamlessdocs.com/f/JRJtFk

We have a wonderful foster program available (if you live inside city limits) to see if the animal compliments or complicates your life. This is an excellent way to see how the pet would get along with family members and other pets! The paperwork takes just a few minutes and you can walk out the door worry free with a fuzzy friend. Call today to inquire more about how you can take this pet home! If you are adopting this cutie, contact the shelter for adoption fees. The Shelter hours are Mon, Tues, Thurs, Fri, 11-5 and Saturday 10-3 closed on Sun and Wed. Our number is 479-524-6535. All animals will be spayed/neuter before going to their new home

animal.description:
Buster - in Maine - updated January 2021

Buster is a 14-15 year old tan Pekingese who recently lost his human mom. This senior sweetie can be a bit anxious but he is managing well in his foster home. He has one eye and has developed some incontinence in his senior years so he uses a belly band when in the house to catch any dribbles. He LOVES to walk and goes for 3 short jaunts a day; he doesn’t run marathons at his age with arthritis in his little hips but he does love to explore. He is such a loving and fun little sweetheart; we’d love to see him have a retirement home where he could be doted on. He uses eye drops to help the remaining eye stay healthy and a medication to help him feel less anxious. He is groomed every 3 months to keep him in tip-top shape, you can tell he has been so loved! It is important that Buster have someone home the majority of the time. Besides walks, he loves to have his cheeks rubbed, to be snuggled and carried, and to eat cooked chicken! His zest for life is obvious when you meet him.

Buster loves people of all ages; he has not been around cats that we know of. When he meets a new dog he barks at them for a while then makes friends. Change can be hard for this little old man so we want to be sure that an individual or family is ready to transition him slowly into a new life.

If you have interest in meeting Buster or any of our cuties, please fill out the adoption application here: http://www.luckypuprescue.org/adoption-application.

Please note: we do not have a physical facility where our dogs are housed; they are cared for in our wonderful foster network throughout New England. It is our expectation that, once approved, a potential family will meet the dog(s) in the foster setting where they are feeling safe and loved.

Thank you for considering rescue!

animal.description:
Hi, I am King. I am a super good looking 8 month old black/rust male Doberman with natural ears and a docked tail.  I currently weigh about 60 lbs, but I am still growing.  
Since I am so young, DAR&E requires that I have a fenced yard. No invisible fences. I am very sweet and LOVE to cuddle and snuggle with my people. If you are looking for a velcro buddy I am your guy!  I love people and know not to jump on people when they visit. 
I am still a puppy but I try to be a good puppy!  I am hoping for a family that will help me continue to learn how grown-up dobes are expected to act.  I learn fast and really want to make my new family proud of me!  
I am already house-trained and I love my crate when it’s bedtime. I even know how to ring a bell to let you know I need to go out! My foster mom is teaching me some basic obedience, but I will need someone who has the time and patience to continue my training. 
I love playing with my foster mom's 3 dogs so a home with a dog or 2 that likes to play would be so much fun! I have lots of puppy energy to burn. I think cats are so much fun to chase, but my foster mom said no cats for me. I guess the cats don't think it’s as much fun as I do. Well, there you go. That’s me in a nutshell, as they say!  If you are up for a young, exciting pup like me, email my foster mom to arrange to meet me. 

DAR&E places dogs in MD, DC, VA and parts of WVA only.  
If you are interested in this pet please follow the link below to read about our adoption process and submit an adoption application.  (copy and paste)  
https://www.dobe.net/adoption/adoption-process/

animal.description:
Puddin's life philosophy: There are no strangers here; Only friends you haven't yet met

(William Butler Yeats)
Hi! I'm Puddin' and I'm a lover: Adults, children, dogs, cats I love everyone!
Besides being adorable and a social butterfly, I am a playful, happy puppy. I love to snuggle,
get hugs, go for walks, play tug, chew on stick chews, nylabones and deer antlers, filled kongs
are yummy during crate time, and really, I like all toys. Oh and my BFF, Frankie! I love going to
Frankie's house for play time!
I am kennel trained, sleep there at night and have never had an accident in the crate.
Sometimes, my foster mom is in a meeting and can't take me out when I need to go, so I use
the puppy pad she puts down for me.
I hope you love me so far and can overlook my one imperfection. You see, something
happened to my foot when I was very young and I didn't get medical attention. All the bones in
my left foot were broken and didn't heal properly. That's why I stand like a ballerina. The nice
people at Needy Paws took me to a surgeon who thought he could fix me, but he couldn't. It
doesn't slow me down. I can still run and play and do all the other puppy things, but I will need
to be on joint supplements for the rest of my life.
So if you like taking walks and will take the time to train me, I will be your lifelong, loving
companion.
Love,
Puddin'

If interested, please
complete the
Adoption Application
on our website at
www.NeedyPaws.org
and we will contact you.
Adopters must live within an hour's drive of St. Louis, MO.

Our $250 adoption fee includes up-to-date vaccinations, heartworm testing and preventative, spay/neuter and microchip.

We are a 100% foster-based rescue and all of our dogs live in approved foster homes. We are dedicated to finding the best Forever Homes, and will perform home visits and conduct veterinarian and reference checks for each potential adopter.

animal.description:
Hi there!  Have you been looking for a bonded pair of cuties?  If so, Stella and Cole are waiting for you! They initially came into rescue after being found abandoned on a country road at about 7 months old.  Both were adopted individually but, sadly, did not adjust well in their homes so they were returned to their foster dad where they were (and are again) happy.  He has concluded that they need a home where they can remain together.

These cuties are Chihuahua / Beagle mix pups.  They’re 1 year old and both weigh in at about 20 pounds.
Stella (red collar) shows more of the beagle side.  Cole (blue collar) is more of a mixture.  Both are playful and friendly with people and fine with kids.  They can be high strung at times so we think older kids would be the best fit.   

They get along well with the other dogs in their foster home and enjoy playing with them – even the big ones. They do get bossy when food is around so we believe the ideal situation for them will be as the only pets in their forever home.  A fenced yard will be perfect because these energizer bunnies love to be outdoors and run around.  Just leash walking a couple times daily is probably not enough to keep them adequately exercised.  Both Stella and Cole are crate trained and leash trained.  They are basically house trained, though they still need some watching.  Stella sometimes has a submissive “tinkle” and Cole occasionally marks inside, but with a regular routine and positive reinforcement, they’ll do fine.

Both Stella and Cole have been spayed and neutered.  They are also up to date on vaccines and microchipped.  Their doggy bags are packed and they can’t wait to learn that their forever home has been found.  If you’d like to double your pleasure and fun with these two cuties, please email   Alyson at alysonbrunelli@gmail.com (include phone number) for an application and she’ll get one right out to you.  The adoption fee for the pair is $450.

Like us on Facebook at www.facebook.com/pawsclawsnewengland

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Eastwood! I am a super sweet, super fun Lab mix; approximately 5 years old and I weigh 57 lbs. I was found as a stray a few years back and some cool folks loaded me up in their car and brought me to ARFhouse! When I arrived I had heartworms but the girls had me treated and now I'm happy, healthy and ready for my forever home! 

I am a spunky boy; I love to run and play! I do well on a leash but could use some 'fine-tuning'. I am a happy, friendly boy, but I look to my humans for confidence in new surroundings. I am eager to please and I love to snuggle and give all the kisses! I am a big, frisky boy and would not be suited for an apartment. I will need a large, fenced yard so that I can run and play anytime I want! I would love to go on long walks or runs with my humans, play ball in the yard and snuggle up on the couch to watch a movie at the end of a long day. 

The fee to adopt Eastwood is $200.00; this includes: neuter, vaccines, deworming and a microchip. 

**Please Note: Eastwood is currently located at our facility in Sherman, TX. Adoptions are BY-APPOINTMENT ONLY. If you are interested in adopting Eastwood, please visit our website, www.arfhouse.org and fill out an adoption application. Once we have your application, our Adoption Coordinator will follow up with you to discuss any questions she may have, or to schedule a time for you to meet Eastwood.

Some of our dogs have also had heartworm tests, flea treatments, canine influenza vaccines, etc., but it is not standard procedure - please inquire about the specific animal you are interested in.

We do adopt out-of-state, but require adopters to meet the pet prior to taking it home. The adopters also must have a plan for getting their new addition home before we process an application. We are open Monday - Friday 11:00 am to 5 pm. You can also call us at 719-680-2385. To fill out the adoption application online please visit our website at noahsarktrinidad.org where you can then email the application with your inquiry.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Name: Mikasa
Age: DOB Approx. 10/07/18
Gender: Female
Breed: Pitty
Weight: 52
Dog friendly: Yes
Cat friendly: TBD
Kid friendly: Yes
House Trained: Yes
Crate Trained: Working on it
Energy level: Moderate
History: pulled from an animal control
Adoption Fee: $500

From the Foster:

If your life could use a little extra sunshine and happiness, please take a moment to read about this ray of sunshine known as Mikasa. You can't help but smile when you're around her, thanks to her sweet demeanor, constantly wagging tail, and the abundance of kisses she tries to shower you with. She is such a friendly dog, to both people and other dogs. If she had her way, she would be next to you or on you at all times. She is that much of a lover, and really wants to be with her person as much as possible. To put it simply, Mikasa just wants to love and be loved in return.

Mikasa's absolute favorite thing to do is play with my resident dog, which she has yet to tire of. She plays hard and as often as possible, so it's important that any dog(s) in her future home would be a good match for her play style and energy needs. Even though I know she would LOVE to have a dog sibling in her furever home, I think she would be okay as an only dog if given plenty of socialization opportunities with other dogs. She is a very active girl and needs a lot of physical and mental stimulation throughout the day. She is not the type of dog who wants to hang out and sleep the day away. She is going to live her life to the fullest and wants to take advantage of every second of every day. Mikasa loves to spend time outdoors and actually jumps in the air when I ask if she wants to go outside. Having a yard she can romp around in would be a huge plus for her.

Now for the fun stuff! Mikasa is potty-trained and does very well doing her business on walks and in my yard, though she does prefer to get things done in the yard. We are working on leash training since she is a strong pup who loves to pull on walks, especially if she sees a squirrel or rabbit. She has made excellent progress on her crate training and has now decided that her crate is a comfy and safe space. She sleeps soundly in her crate every night and is crated when I have to leave the house. Mikasa doesn't want to miss out on anything, so if she knows you're off doing something without her, she can be very vocal. Because of this, I don't think shared walls would be the best living situation for her. With patience, love, positive training, and some really tasty treats, I know Mikasa will truly thrive in the right home.

Mikasa is pending some medical care but still available for adoption. She has bilateral (both sides) grade 2/4 luxating patellas on her rear knees and will need 2 orthopedic surgeries completed by a specialist at the SHH Vet Center.

The recovery period requires strict rest and restricted activity for 12 weeks *per surgery* so any adopter just needs to be aware of this care and treatment. The estimated amount of time with surgery and recovery is 6+ months for both procedures.

Miksasa will be adopted with an FTA (foster to adopt) contract so the adoption can take place, while SHH still manages the financial responsibility of my orthopedic surgery. Any other medical care needed outside of these surgeries
covered by the FTA contract
would be the responsibility of the adopter.

Online Adoption Application 

Mini is very sweet and looking for someone to love. She loves to sit 'right' next to you and will inch closer and closer. She is a lap dog and loves being carried. She loves her people so much; she will bark at strangers until she warms up. Mini is housetrained and waits by the door to go out. She is fostered with other small dogs and tolerates them. She does get possessive (growling) about food around other dogs (never people), but the dogs she is fostered with are not threatened by her tiny size and usually just ignore her. She likes cats. Her real passion is 'her' people. She enjoys sleeping in, cuddled up under the blankets with someone she adores. She is fostered with several children and prefers kids over 10. She also likes adults. She enjoys to be petted by younger children, but will growl if they try to pick her up or move her. She has not nipped at anyone in her foster house (other than the male dog she is fostered with). She is vocal and will ask for attention, love, and snacks. If you ask her a question, she will likely speak back to you. Her bark is rather gruff for her size (not too shrill). She likes to play. She enjoys going for a walk on a leash. Though she is rarely crated in her foster home, she will bark until you leave or if you are in sight. She will settle down quickly in her crate if you leave her a warm and comfy bed.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Oz is ready for adoption! He is a beautiful brindle and whit French Bulldog. Oz is about 6 - 7 years old and weighs 25 pounds. He does have medical needs so please read his profile carefully.

Oz came to us a few months ago with some major medical needs. He had severe ear infections, a cauliflower ear, underweight and a major tumor on his front leg. Fattening him up was easy! We took care of his ears but please understand that he will likely have issues in the future. He will need to have his ears cleaned regularly and remain on a quality grain free diet as that has helped. As for the mass, we had it removed and let him heal. The mass was cancerous and will likely return. But it is not a type of cancer that will spread internally. So any lump or bump he gets needs to be looked at right away and biopsied.

Now on to the good stuff! Oz is a charming little toad! He is definitely a foster favorite! He loves people! He loves to get attention and will be your best friend for some ear rubs. Oz is crate trained but his foster mom hardly puts him in it any more. Oz is leash trained. He gets so excited when he sees the leash! He is very good in the car too. Oz is nicely housetrained but you do have to do some convincing to get him up in the morning. Lazy bulldog! Please expect some adjustment time though as he learns a new home and routine. He does have a fully fenced yard in his foster home, which he loves in nice weather. Oz is good with other dogs but like a typical bulldog, will give an occasional "get out of my space" jab, usually towards puppies. Oz has no issues with cats, in fact they like to clean his face for him! Oz gets his face washed by his foster mom to help keep his wrinkles and creases clean. He loves that. Oz comes when he is called and sits nicely for a treat. Cheese is a favorite for this Frenchie. Oz makes lots of noises - he snores like a champ! Bulldog experience is preferred but not required.

A lot of people think they want a bulldog but do not realize that they are an expensive, quirky dogs! Between food and vet care, please expect to spend more then you ever had on a dog. Oz has many years left to him but only if he will be well taken care of. We will not compromise on the home we are looking for him.

Oz is neutered, up to date with vaccines, microchipped, and tested neg. for heartworm. His adoption fee is $350

Because we require home checks adoptions are limited to the Los Angeles, Ca area.

animal.description:
**If you're interested in learning more about Skype, please email xgenic@gmail.com**

Hey there! My name is Skype...why do they call me that? Probably because I love to say Hi to everyone, whether they walk on two legs or four. I get lots of comments wherever I go because people love my short stubby legs and my spotted face. I've shared living space with lots of doggie roommates and do well as long as they don't get too bossy. I'm not a big fan of being told what to do. I also like children but they get me over-stimulated with loud noises and fast movements, so I'd prefer a house with older kids that know how to respect a dog's boundaries. 

I absolutely love to run and play in water. I hope my new family has a lake, or a river, or a plastic swimming pool, or even a water hose? Surprisingly though, I'm afraid to walk through puddles on the sidewalk or go out in the rain. 

My second favorite hobby is to ride shotgun in the car. I'm always excited to go to new places and I've been working really hard on my self control to remain calm, so I hope you can help me continue to learn. I've gotten pretty good, but I still lose my head whenever a loud motorcycle drives by! 

I love to eat! I spend most of my days thinking about food but I've lost 6lbs through hard work and dedication. I'm now at a very sexy 66lbs. I'll walk very calmly by your side without pulling on the leash and I really enjoy working out with the occasional sprint (but not very far because my legs are so short). After a good exercise, I'll sprawl out on the floor and enjoy a good belly rub or rump scratch.

Are you ready to help me keep my New Year Resolution to stay in shape?

As with many mature dogs, we are recommending that Prudence be on long-term daily joint supplements, as she does have some mild hip dysplasia, however with the right amount of exercise, weight management and the supplements, she is feeling and looking great! animal.description:
Surrendered to animal control by her owners due to an eviction in September of 2020, Leah spent her 2 years of life from puppyhood on a chain tied to a barrel and being bred repeatedly. Upon arrival she refused to come out of the animal control truck and our trainer had to spend some time gaining tiny bits of trust in order to carry her down to her kennel without causing Leah to panic. It took days for our trainer to gain enough trust to even give Leah a tiny scratch on her ear. Leah has been through our Slow Track Training Program and is now walking with volunteers on a leash, playing with groups of dogs, and bravely meeting new people. Leah finds so much joy in actually running and playing, little things that were denied to her until now. 

Leah is a very special girl needing a special home. She loves the companionship of other dogs and gets along well with cats. She is still timid and cannot go to a home with children under the age of 10. She will also need a home with a securely fenced in yard. Once she knows you, she loves attention and cuddling. We would love for Leah's potential adopters to come spend some time with her during 1-2 meetings before taking her home. 

If you are interested in Leah, please fill out an adoption application online through our website, foothillshumanesociety.org.
